export const STYLE_PROMPTS = new Map([
  ["hyper_graphite", "[SUBJECT].\nSTYLE: Hyper-realistic graphite and charcoal masterpiece. Photorealistic precision. 8k resolution.\nLIGHTING & VALUE: Extreme high-contrast chiaroscuro. Deep, burnished charcoal blacks for shadows and ink. Blindingly bright paper-white specular highlights for skin and metal. The contrast should make the subject appear to \"glow\" with three-dimensionality.\nCLARITY: Optical sharpness. Every detail must be crisp. Render individual hair strands, skin pores, and tattoo ink with absolute precision.\nTEXTURE: Fine-grain archival cotton paper. The texture should be visible but the drawing itself must be sharp, not smudged or blurry.\nCOMPOSITION: Subject completely isolated on a clean, off-white paper background (negative space).\nNEGATIVE: blurry, soft focus, airbrush, digital painting style, low contrast, muddy greys, cartoon, anime, smooth, vector."],
  ["80s_chrome", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Vintage 1980s commercial airbrush illustration. Physical acrylic paint on cold-press illustration board. Sorayama-style liquid chrome aesthetic. LIGHTING & VALUE: \"Horizon line\" reflection mapping. The upper half reflects deep cosmic black, the lower half reflects a glowing neon grid or desert landscape. High-voltage starburst lens flares on metallic edges. CLARITY: Analog high-fidelity scan. The sharpness comes from the masking tape edges used in airbrushing, not digital pixels. Smooth, sprayed gradients. TEXTURE: Glossy automotive enamel finish mixed with the slight grain of physical canvas board. COMPOSITION: Subject centered and imposing, floating in a star-field void. NEGATIVE: 3D render, digital painting, 8k, noise, pixelated, flat, vector, modern cgi, plastic skin, soft focus."],
  ["90s_noir", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: 1990s avant-garde fashion photography. \"Heroin chic\" aesthetic. Cross-processed 35mm film stock. LIGHTING & VALUE: Harsh, direct ring-flash lighting. Center-weighted brightness that falls off rapidly into deep, crushed blacks. Cold chemical color grading (cobalt blue and sickly green shadows). High contrast and moody. CLARITY: Optical lens sharpness. Focus is razor sharp on the center, with slight chromatic aberration on the edges. Defined film grain, not digital noise. TEXTURE: Wet-look latex, glossy vinyl, and damp skin. The image should feel \"slick\" and industrial. COMPOSITION: Subject isolated against a pitch-black or midnight blue velvet backdrop. NEGATIVE: sunlight, warm tones, sepia, painterly, illustration, sketch, 8k, hdr, smooth, cartoon, anime."],
  ["y2k_fluid", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: High-end 2000s CGI render. Ray-traced liquid mercury and hyper-viscous water simulations. The aesthetic of an early Nvidia tech demo or Y2K futuristic magazine design (Frutiger Aero). LIGHTING & VALUE: Global Illumination with a high-contrast HDRI reflection map. The lighting comes entirely from the environment reflecting off the subject. Blinding white specular highlights on the crests of liquid ripples. \"Caustics\" (light refraction) projecting onto the shadows. CLARITY: Anti-aliased vector perfection. Razor-sharp, glass-like edges. No film grain or texture—just pure, smooth digital surfaces. TEXTURE: Physically Based Rendering (PBR) materials: Flawless mirror-finish chrome, transparent glass, and clear water. The silver must look \"wet\" and heavy. COMPOSITION: Subject suspended in a zero-gravity \"white void\" or soft silver gradient studio space. NEGATIVE: dry, matte, textured paper, sketch, noise, grain, dirt, rust, organic imperfections, low resolution, blurry, 8k, photorealism."],
  ["engraving", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: 17th-Century Copperplate Engraving and Etching. Albrecht Dürer and Gustave Doré aesthetic. Ink on aged parchment. LIGHTING & VALUE: Value is created entirely through cross-hatching and line density, not smooth shading. Deep, heavy ink for shadows, sparse lines for mid-tones, and bare paper for highlights. CLARITY: Archival print definition. Every line must be distinct and separate (woodcut style). No smudging or grey wash. TEXTURE: Intaglio print texture. The lines should feel \"carved\" into the paper. COMPOSITION: Subject isolated on a creamy, antique paper background with faint foxing. NEGATIVE: smooth shading, gradients, pencil, charcoal, blur, photo, realism, 3d render, digital art, color, 8k."],
  ["dotwork", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Sacred Geometry and Stippling (Dotwork). Mathematical precision. Technical drawing aesthetic. LIGHTING & VALUE: Gradients achieved solely through dot density (Pointillism). Soft, ambient occlusion created by millions of individual ink dots. No solid lines for shading, only for outlines. CLARITY: Macro definition. Individual dots must be visible and distinct. Perfect, razor-sharp geometric outlines (circles, hexagons, golden ratio). TEXTURE: Archival ink on smooth bristol board. Clean and clinical. COMPOSITION: Subject integrated with geometric diagrams and mandala overlays on a pure white background. NEGATIVE: hatching, sketchy, messy, wash, watercolor, painting, solid shading, blurry, 8k."],
  ["sculpture", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Classical Renaissance Marble Sculpture. Michelangelo and Bernini aesthetic. Carved Carrara marble. LIGHTING & VALUE: Museum spot-lighting. Soft, diffused shadows that define the muscle and drapery. \"Subsurface scattering\" (light penetrating the stone slightly) to make the marble look waxy and realistic. CLARITY: Chiseled sharpness. Cracks, chips, and tool marks should be visible in high definition. TEXTURE: Porous, cold stone with a matte finish. Slight weathering and dust in the crevices. COMPOSITION: Subject presented as a bust or statue on a dark grey studio background. NEGATIVE: flesh, skin, color, wet, shiny, metallic, cartoon, illustration, sketching, pencil, 8k."],
  ["surreal", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Cinematic Double Exposure Photography. True Detective opening credits aesthetic. Silhouette blended with nature. LIGHTING & VALUE: High-contrast silhouette. The \"inside\" of the subject is filled with a secondary image (forests, galaxies, ocean waves) that glows. Moody, atmospheric backlighting. CLARITY: Crystal clear edges for the silhouette, but the interior details are dreamy and ethereal. TEXTURE: Film grain and photographic emulsion. Mist and fog elements. COMPOSITION: Subject silhouette centered on a stark white or light grey background to ensure the stencil is readable. NEGATIVE: flat, cartoon, vector, thick lines, simple, solid fill, boring, 8k."],
  ["sumie", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Traditional Japanese Sumi-e Ink Wash painting. Expressive brushwork. Zen minimalist aesthetic. LIGHTING & VALUE: Extreme contrast between \"wet\" heavy black ink and \"dry\" sweeping brush tails. Uses negative space (Ma) as a highlight. No complex lighting, just the weight of the ink. CLARITY: Texture of the brush hairs must be visible. Edges are organic and rough, not mathematically perfect. TEXTURE: Bleeding ink on fibrous rice paper (Washi). Visible paper grain. COMPOSITION: Asymmetrical and flowing. Subject isolated on textured white paper. NEGATIVE: pencil, shading, gradients, photorealism, 3d, chrome, geometric, stiff, rigid, plastic, 8k."],
  ["donatello", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: High-Renaissance marble sculpture masterpiece. Carved Carrara marble texture. In the style of Donatello and Bernini. Museum quality photography. LIGHTING & VALUE: Soft, diffused museum skylight illumination. Gentle ambient occlusion in the folds of drapery. The lighting should emphasize the translucency of the marble (subsurface scattering), making the stone appear soft and skin-like. CLARITY: Razor-sharp focus on material details. Visible chisel marks and fine surface grain. The edges of the sculpture should be distinct against the background. TEXTURE: Porous, crystalline marble grain. Occasional weathering, cracks, or patina consistent with ancient preservation. Dust in deep crevices. COMPOSITION: Subject is a static statue, isolated on a neutral, dark velvet or museum-grey background to maximize contrast with the white stone. Dramatic, emotive posing. NEGATIVE: living flesh, skin tone, color photography, modern clothes, plastic, wax, 3D render, low poly, blurry, noise, grain, text, watermark."],
  ["biomech", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Biomechanical surrealism. H.R. Giger meets Hajime Sorayama. A fusion of organic anatomy and industrial machinery. Airbrush and oil on canvas. LIGHTING & VALUE: Cold, harsh, cinematic lighting. Rim lighting to accentuate silhouettes. Deep, void-like shadows contrasting with high-specular highlights on metallic surfaces. The value range is compressed into dark greys and bright silvers. CLARITY: Hyper-detailed. Every tube, wire, and rib must be rendered with blueprint precision. Infinite depth of field—background details are as sharp as the foreground. TEXTURE: Wet, slimy organic surfaces juxtaposed with polished chrome and matte rubber. The image should evoke a tactile sensation of coldness and moisture. COMPOSITION: Symmetrical, cathedral-like framing. The subject is integrated into a complex, repetitive background pattern of pipes and vertebrae. NEGATIVE: warm colors, sunlight, fuzzy, impressionist, sketch, simplistic, cartoon, joyful, soft, wood texture, nature, flowers."],
  ["riso", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Vintage Risograph print / DIY Zine aesthetic. Limited color palette (Cyan, Fluorescent Pink, Yellow, Black). Coarse halftone dot shading. LIGHTING & VALUE: Flat lighting. No realistic shadows. Form is defined by overlapping fields of solid color and varying densities of halftone patterns. High-key, bright, and punchy. CLARITY: Intentionally lo-fi. Visible paper grain and printer misalignment (registration errors). Edges are rough and organic, mimicking ink bleed. TEXTURE: Uncoated paper texture. The \"noise\" of the image is constituted by the distinct rosette patterns of the printing process. Dithering artifacts. COMPOSITION: Graphic design layout. Bold, flat shapes. Subject is often collaged or silhouetted against a solid or patterned background. NEGATIVE: 3D render, glossy, realistic lighting, gradients, smooth shading, 4k, hdr, photography, bokeh, depth of field, muted colors."],
  ["dark_fantasy", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Vintage 1970s dark fantasy oil painting. Frank Frazetta and Boris Vallejo influence. Masterful anatomical rendering. Physical canvas texture. LIGHTING & VALUE: Dramatic \"Rembrandt\" lighting with a fantasy twist. Deep, murky shadows concealing threats. Warm, glowing highlights (orange/gold) striking the subject's muscles and armor. High contrast between the focal point and the void. CLARITY: Painterly realism. Visible brushstrokes, particularly in the background, but the subject is rendered with anatomical precision. Soft edges to suggest motion. TEXTURE: Heavy linen canvas weave. Thick impasto paint application in highlights. An aged, varnished look (yellowing) to the overall palette. COMPOSITION: Pyramidal composition. The subject dominates the frame, often looking down at the viewer or fighting an unseen enemy. Dynamic, swirling background clouds or smoke. NEGATIVE: anime, cartoon, digital art, flat, vector, bright day, clean, modern, photograph, 3D render, plastic looking skin."],
  ["alcohol_ink", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Macro photography of alcohol ink and gold leaf fluid art. Abstract expressionism. Ethereal and fluid. LIGHTING & VALUE: Backlit translucency. The light seems to shine *through* the liquid, making colors vibrant and jewel-like. High-key brightness with sharp metallic reflections on gold veins. CLARITY: Macro focus. Extreme detail on the fluid dynamics—micro-bubbles, pigment separation, and capillary action. Soft, dreamlike blur in the periphery. TEXTURE: Liquid gloss. Smooth, flowing gradients interrupted by hard, metallic edges (gold/copper leaf). No grain, just fluid turbulence. COMPOSITION: Organic and flowing. No rigid structure. The subject is often dissolved into the flow, represented as a silhouette or a formation within the ink. NEGATIVE: geometric, rigid, straight lines, solid, dry, sketched, pencil, charcoal, dull, matte, photography of people."],
  ["kodachrome", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Vintage 1970s analog photography. Kodak Kodachrome film stock. Candid snapshot aesthetic. Stephen Shore and William Eggleston influence. LIGHTING & VALUE: Natural, harsh sunlight (golden hour or high noon). Hard shadows. \"Crushed\" blacks with little detail in the shadows. Warm, nostalgic color cast (yellow/magenta bias). CLARITY: Soft analog sharpness. Not clinically sharp like digital. Slight lens softness in the corners (vignetting). TEXTURE: Visible film grain (ISO 400). Chemical color noise. Slight dust and scratches on the negative. COMPOSITION: Candid, unposed framing. Slightly imperfect horizons. \"Snapshot\" aesthetic—capturing a fleeting moment of everyday life. NEGATIVE: hd, 4k, digital, sharp, clean, studio lighting, cgi, render, modern, cooler colors, perfect composition, retouching."],
  ["art_nouveau", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Psychedelic Art Nouveau. Alphonse Mucha meets Wes Wilson. 1960s concert poster aesthetic. Intricate line work and organic flow. LIGHTING & VALUE: Flat illumination. No shadows. The \"vibration\" comes from Clashing Colors (Red next to Green). Gold leaf accents. CLARITY: stylized line art. Fluid, melting lines. Everything connects to everything else. TEXTURE: Matte poster paper. Screen print texture. COMPOSITION: The \"Halo\" composition. Subject centered with a circular stained-glass background. Hair and fabric turn into borders and flowers. NEGATIVE: photo, real, 3d, minimalist, empty, grid, straight lines, tech, modern."],
  ["pop_art", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: 1960s Pop Art. Roy Lichtenstein style. Vintage comic book panel. Ben-Day dots for shading. LIGHTING & VALUE: Flat, commercial lighting. Shadows are rendered as solid black shapes or fields of heavy dots. No nuance—it is either lit or unlit. CLARITY: Vector-like sharpness. Bold, uniform black outlines. Perfect geometric circles for the dot patterns. TEXTURE: Newsprint texture. The cheap paper used in vintage comics. Slight yellowing. COMPOSITION: Close-up, dramatic cropping. Speech bubbles or action lines (\"POW!\"). Melodramatic facial expressions. NEGATIVE: realistic, painterly, soft, gradient, 3d, textured, grayscale, muted, subtle."],
  ["dark_engraving", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Dark fantasy copperplate engraving masterpiece. Intricate cross-hatching and intaglio linework rendered in ink-black on aged parchment. 8k resolution. --sref 1243837571\nLIGHTING & VALUE: Dramatic chiaroscuro with deep engraved shadow channels and stark highlight ridges. Dense parallel hatch lines build volumetric form. Brightest areas emerge as untouched paper between line clusters, creating a luminous glow against suffocating darkness.\nCLARITY: Every cross-hatch line must be individually legible. Render each strand of hair, each scale, each wrinkle with obsessive engraver's precision. No blur, no softness.\nTEXTURE: Hammered copper-plate impression on heavy cotton rag. Visible ink-press depth and plate-tone variation. Lines have slight burr and tooth from the engraving burin.\nCOMPOSITION: Subject isolated on clean parchment background. Gothic, macabre, and fantastical subject matter rendered with anatomical authority.\nNEGATIVE: smooth gradients, airbrush, digital painting, soft shading, blurry, watercolor, cartoon, flat color, low detail, pencil sketch."],
  ["linocut", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Bold black-and-white linocut printmaking masterpiece. Hand-carved woodblock aesthetic with high-contrast graphic authority. 8k resolution. --sref 1783140040\nLIGHTING & VALUE: Pure binary contrast — solid ink-black masses against raw paper-white. No grey tones, no gradients. Shadow is total darkness, light is total absence of ink. Every form is defined by the knife-edge boundary between black and white.\nCLARITY: Razor-sharp carved edges. Each gouge mark and cut line must read as deliberate and decisive. Organic textures from the block-printing process. No softness, no anti-aliasing.\nTEXTURE: Visible wood-grain impression and lino-gouge tool marks. Slight ink bleed at edges where block meets paper. Handmade print imperfections — minor registration shifts and ink density variation.\nCOMPOSITION: Subject isolated on clean white paper ground. Surreal symbolism, skulls, masks, organic and geometric forms interlocking.\nNEGATIVE: smooth digital rendering, gradients, grey tones, photorealistic, airbrushed, blurry, soft edges, watercolor washes, pencil sketch."],
  ["sumi_brush", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Expressive Japanese sumi-e ink and brush painting masterpiece. Bold calligraphic brushstrokes with gestural energy and atmospheric depth. 8k resolution. --sref 877890516\nLIGHTING & VALUE: Dynamic ink-wash value range from explosive carbon-black dry-brush strokes to whisper-thin grey washes dissolving into bare rice paper. Dramatic negative space drives the composition. The power is in what is left unpainted.\nCLARITY: Each brushstroke must read as a single, confident, irreversible gesture — thick to thin, wet to dry. Visible bristle tracks, splatter, and ink pooling. No blending, no overworking.\nTEXTURE: Absorbent washi rice paper with visible fiber. Ink bleeds softly at edges where wet brush meets paper. Dry-brush strokes reveal the paper grain beneath. Controlled accidents of ink and water.\nCOMPOSITION: Subject emerging from vast negative space on off-white rice paper. Asymmetrical balance. Dramatic atmospheric perspective through ink density.\nNEGATIVE: digital painting, smooth rendering, photorealistic, heavy color, airbrushed, symmetrical, overworked, blurry, cartoon, vector, gradient fills."],
  ["stipple", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Meticulous black-and-white stipple and dotwork masterpiece. Thousands of individually placed ink dots build form, value, and atmosphere. 8k resolution. --sref 4083089919\nLIGHTING & VALUE: Full tonal range constructed entirely from dot density — from impenetrable clustered-dot blacks to single scattered dots fading into paper-white. No solid fills, no continuous lines. Every shadow is a galaxy of points. Every highlight is the paper breathing through sparse dots.\nCLARITY: Each individual dot must be visible and distinct at close inspection. Macro-level precision. The stipple pattern must never blur into smooth tone — the pointillistic construction must always be legible.\nTEXTURE: Heavy archival paper with slight tooth. Ink dots sit cleanly on surface. Visible variation in dot size creates organic depth. Hand-placed irregularity, not mechanical halftone.\nCOMPOSITION: Subject isolated on clean white ground. Moody, atmospheric, contemplative subjects rendered with halftone-like tonal sophistication.\nNEGATIVE: solid lines, smooth shading, gradients, airbrush, color, watercolor, blurry, digital painting, continuous tone, pencil, charcoal smudge."],
  ["art_nouveau_gold", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Intricate Art Nouveau ornamental masterpiece. Symmetrical, curvilinear compositions with bold expressive linework, floral motifs, and mystical elegance. 8k resolution. --sref 3553079091\nLIGHTING & VALUE: Predominantly monochromatic — rich blacks, warm whites, and burnished gold accents. Deep shadows in ornamental borders frame luminous central figures. Gold leaf detailing catches light with metallic brilliance against matte black backgrounds.\nCLARITY: Every decorative tendril, every petal curve, every geometric border must be rendered with jeweler's precision. Hair-thin filigree lines must remain crisp alongside bold contour strokes. Absolute sharpness at every scale.\nTEXTURE: Smooth bristol board surface for crisp linework. Gold-foil metallic accents. The quality of hand-inked illustration with architectural drafting precision. Clean, deliberate, ornamental.\nCOMPOSITION: Symmetrical framing with decorative borders. Central figure surrounded by organic flowing patterns. Stained-glass-window structure meets Alphonse Mucha elegance.\nNEGATIVE: rough sketch, messy, asymmetrical chaos, photorealistic, airbrushed, blurry, watercolor, cartoon, low detail, flat design, digital gradients."],
  ["botanical", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Highly detailed botanical fine-line illustration masterpiece. Intricate pen-and-ink linework with scientific precision and imaginative depth. 8k resolution. --sref 3614140049\nLIGHTING & VALUE: Delicate monochromatic tonal range built through line weight variation alone — no washes, no shading fills. Thicker contour lines define form while whisper-thin interior lines describe veins, texture, and cellular detail. Light areas are simply less line density.\nCLARITY: Absolute optical precision. Every leaf vein, every petal edge, every stamen filament rendered with botanical-plate accuracy. Individual line strokes must be traceable. The illustration must reward extreme close-up inspection.\nTEXTURE: Smooth hot-press illustration board. Clean india-ink lines with no feathering or bleed. The pristine quality of a Victorian-era natural history plate. Archival, precise, timeless.\nCOMPOSITION: Subject isolated on clean white background. Layered organic compositions with overlapping flora creating visual depth. Scientific accuracy meets fantastical imagination.\nNEGATIVE: thick outlines, cartoon, blurry, watercolor, color fills, digital painting, airbrushed, rough sketch, charcoal, smudged, low detail, flat."],
  ["sacred_geometry", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Intricate sacred geometry and cosmic mandala masterpiece. Precise geometric patterns blending esoteric symbolism with futuristic, visionary aesthetics. 8k resolution. --sref 1884814882\nLIGHTING & VALUE: Luminous neon-blue and gold linework radiating against deep cosmic black. Geometric forms glow with inner light — bright line edges fade into dark voids. Radial symmetry creates a hypnotic focal point of pure brilliance at center, dimming toward ornate peripheral structures.\nCLARITY: Mathematical precision. Every line, arc, and intersection must be geometrically perfect. Razor-thin construction lines, precise compass curves, and exact angular measurements. The complexity must remain legible at every zoom level.\nTEXTURE: Polished obsidian-black ground with luminous line overlay. The quality of laser-etched crystal or precision-machined metal. Clean, otherworldly, immaculate. No organic imperfections.\nCOMPOSITION: Radially symmetrical mandala structure centered on the frame. Concentric rings of increasing complexity. Fibonacci spirals, Metatron's cube, flower of life, platonic solids.\nNEGATIVE: organic roughness, hand-drawn wobble, watercolor, sketch, blurry, cartoon, photorealistic, earth tones, muted colors, messy, asymmetrical."],
  ["watercolor_splash", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Expressive ink-and-watercolor splash masterpiece. Bold gestural brushwork with vibrant bleeding colors and controlled chaos. 8k resolution. --sref 2099337199\nLIGHTING & VALUE: High contrast between deep carbon-black ink lines and explosive saturated watercolor bursts. Ink provides structural skeleton, color provides emotional atmosphere. Brightest pigment bleeds radiate outward from the subject like floral explosions against white paper.\nCLARITY: Ink contour lines must be sharp and decisive. Watercolor washes flow freely with authentic wet-on-wet bleeding and pigment granulation. The contrast between precise linework and chaotic color splashes is the defining tension.\nTEXTURE: Cold-press watercolor paper with visible tooth and grain. Pigment pools in paper valleys. Salt-crystal blooming effects. Drip runs and capillary ink trails. Authentic wet-media behavior — not digitally simulated.\nCOMPOSITION: Subject anchored by bold ink drawing, surrounded by radiating watercolor splashes on white paper. Color breaks free of the drawn boundaries. Negative space is essential.\nNEGATIVE: flat digital color, airbrushed, photorealistic, smooth gradients, vector, cartoon, muddy colors, overworked, blurry ink lines, symmetrical, contained."],
  ["dark_gothic", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Dark gothic surrealist masterpiece. Monochromatic sepia-toned illustration with bold linework and macabre fantastical imagery. 8k resolution. --sref 1630292538\nLIGHTING & VALUE: Oppressive chiaroscuro in desaturated earth tones — deep charcoal blacks, ashen greys, and aged-bone whites. Dramatic directional lighting carves subjects from surrounding darkness. Occasional warm sepia accents in midtones. The atmosphere must feel heavy, ominous, and suffocating.\nCLARITY: Detailed rendering of distorted anatomy, decaying textures, and surreal architectural elements. Every crack in bone, every feather on a raven, every thread of cobweb must be precisely articulated. Sharp focus throughout.\nTEXTURE: Aged parchment or toned paper quality. Visible grain and surface patina. The quality of a Victorian-era mezzotint or dark-room photographic print. Weathered, antique, timeworn.\nCOMPOSITION: Asymmetrical, dynamic compositions with dramatic scale shifts. Subject isolated against atmospheric negative space. Gothic architecture, occult symbols, and memento mori elements integrated naturally.\nNEGATIVE: bright colors, cheerful, clean digital art, airbrushed, cartoon, anime, smooth plastic texture, high saturation, modern, minimal, vector."],
  ["blackwork", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Bold blackwork silhouette and stencil-cut masterpiece. Graphic black-on-white and white-on-black compositions with Art Nouveau-inspired organic elegance. 8k resolution. --sref 599127011\nLIGHTING & VALUE: Absolute binary — solid black and solid white only. No grey, no gradients, no halftones. Form is defined purely by the silhouette edge and by negative-space cutouts within black masses. The interplay between positive and negative space IS the entire image.\nCLARITY: Knife-sharp silhouette edges. Every leaf, petal, and figure contour must be crisp enough to cut a stencil from. Interior negative-space details (veins, patterns, features) must be equally precise. Clean enough to laser-cut.\nTEXTURE: Smooth matte black ink on bright white paper. The quality of a precision paper-cut or screen-printed poster. Flat, graphic, absolute. No visible brush marks, no texture within the black — pure solid fill.\nCOMPOSITION: Symmetrical or balanced compositions. Figures framed by decorative floral and organic border elements. Strong use of negative space to define interior detail. Panel and tile-like arrangements.\nNEGATIVE: gradients, grey tones, shading, cross-hatching, watercolor, photorealistic, 3D rendering, texture, rough edges, blurry, soft, pencil, sketch."],
  ["silver_chrome", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Hyper-realistic liquid silver chrome 3D render. Mirror-polished metallic surfaces with organic, flowing sculptural forms. 8k resolution. --sref 4084506961\nLIGHTING & VALUE: Studio-lit chrome reflections — blindingly bright specular hotspots against deep gunmetal shadow pools. Environment reflections warp and stretch across every curved surface. The subject should look like it was dipped in molten mercury and flash-frozen. Extreme dynamic range from black mirror reflections to searing white specular peaks.\nCLARITY: Photographic precision on every chrome reflection, every surface warp, every environmental distortion. Individual reflection edges must be razor-sharp. The metallic surface must feel tangibly polished — zero noise, zero grain.\nTEXTURE: Flawless mirror-finish chrome. Liquid-smooth, impossibly reflective. The cold, precise quality of CNC-machined aerospace aluminum or hand-polished show-car bodywork. No matte, no brushed metal, no satin — pure mirror.\nCOMPOSITION: Subject isolated on neutral dark gradient or pure black background. Dramatic three-quarter lighting to maximize reflective contrast. Art Deco and Futurism influence on pose and form.\nNEGATIVE: matte surface, brushed metal, satin finish, flat lighting, dull grey, plastic, cartoon, painterly, soft focus, warm tones, rust, patina, scratches."],
  ["liquid_mercury", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Liquid metallic sculptural masterpiece. Cool-toned chrome with surrealist, flowing, molten-metal forms that defy gravity. 8k resolution. --sref 3047838275\nLIGHTING & VALUE: Icy blue-silver reflections dominating the palette. Deep cobalt and steel-blue shadows with platinum-white specular highlights. The light source should feel cold and clinical — like a laboratory or glacier. Reflections show distorted landscapes and abstract environments.\nCLARITY: Hyper-real surface detail — every ripple in the liquid metal, every tension line where chrome stretches over form, every micro-reflection must be crisp and defined. The rendering must feel like a high-end 3D production still.\nTEXTURE: Liquid metal in mid-flow — heavier and denser than mercury, thicker than water. Surface tension visible at edges where metal pools and drips. Some areas frozen-smooth, others caught mid-splash with fine metallic tendrils.\nCOMPOSITION: Dramatic figure compositions against minimal dark backgrounds. Neoclassical sculptural poses rendered in impossible liquid metal. The weight and fluidity of the metal should contrast with the frozen-moment stillness.\nNEGATIVE: warm tones, gold, copper, rust, matte, dry surface, cartoon, flat, illustrative, painterly, soft focus, low resolution, plastic, rubber."],
  ["neon_cyberpunk", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Vibrant neon-drenched cyberpunk masterpiece. Synthwave-infused digital art with explosive iridescent color, holographic light trails, and backlit silhouettes against deep darkness. 8k resolution. --sref 2869983106\nLIGHTING & VALUE: Total darkness shattered by intense neon light sources — electric magenta, cyan, toxic green, and ultraviolet purple. Subjects are rim-lit and backlit by multiple neon sources, creating vivid color-bleed halos. Deep blacks in unlit areas provide maximum contrast against searing neon edges. The light itself is the subject.\nCLARITY: Sharp neon edges and clean light trails against crisp dark backgrounds. Lens flare and light bloom are intentional but controlled. Silhouette edges must be knife-sharp where they meet the neon glow. Fine holographic interference patterns in reflective surfaces.\nTEXTURE: Smooth digital rendering with intentional lens artifacts — chromatic aberration at neon edges, bokeh orbs, subtle scanline overlay. The quality of a long-exposure photograph in a neon-lit city. Wet surfaces amplify reflections and color bleeding.\nCOMPOSITION: Dynamic asymmetrical compositions with strong diagonal energy. Subjects emerging from or consumed by neon light against void-black negative space. Speed lines, light trails, and holographic UI overlays.\nNEGATIVE: daylight, natural light, earth tones, muted colors, pastel, flat lighting, pencil, sketch, watercolor, oil painting, vintage, sepia, warm cozy, soft."],
  ["biomech_organic", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Intricate biomechanical masterpiece. Fusion of organic anatomy and alien machine architecture with warm, earthy tones and unsettling hyper-detail. 8k resolution. --sref 1089011115\nLIGHTING & VALUE: Warm amber and bone-white directional lighting raking across complex surface detail. Deep umber and raw-sienna shadows in the recesses between organic tendrils and mechanical housings. Subsurface-scattering glow in translucent membrane areas. The lighting must emphasize every horrifying textural detail — every tendon, every joint, every chitinous plate.\nCLARITY: Obsessive, nightmarish detail at every scale. Macro-level rendering of fibrous muscle strands, insectoid exoskeleton segments, exposed vertebrae, and bio-mechanical tubing. Every surface must reward extreme close-up inspection with more nested complexity. Nothing smooth, nothing simple.\nTEXTURE: Wet organic surfaces — glistening mucous membranes, stretched sinew, pulsing vein networks. Hard surfaces — chitinous shell, calcified bone plates, corroded metal housings. The contrast between wet-organic and dry-mechanical creates maximum visual tension.\nCOMPOSITION: Asymmetrical, sprawling compositions that fill the frame. Subjects appear to be mid-metamorphosis — half-emerged, partially dissected, eternally transforming. No clean backgrounds — organic structures bleed to frame edges.\nNEGATIVE: clean, smooth, polished, cute, cartoon, minimal, digital art, flat color, pastel, friendly, symmetrical, simple, low detail, anime, cheerful."],
  ["glitch_art", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Aggressive digital glitch art masterpiece. Databent, pixel-shifted, and signal-corrupted imagery with violent chromatic separation and structural fragmentation. 8k resolution. --sref 741749237\nLIGHTING & VALUE: Corrupted signal — areas of blown-out white interference bars alternating with crushed-black dead zones. RGB color channels visibly separated and misaligned. Occasional uncorrupted areas create haunting moments of clarity within the chaos. The value structure is deliberately broken — scanlines, banding, and tearing override natural light logic.\nCLARITY: Paradoxical — some areas razor-sharp, others completely destroyed by pixel corruption. Horizontal scanline displacement creates jagged, staircase edges. The subject must be recognizable but damaged, like a surveillance feed under electromagnetic attack. Intentional low-res pixel blocks adjacent to hyper-crisp fragments.\nTEXTURE: CRT scanline overlay, JPEG compression artifacts amplified to visible scale, VHS tracking errors, dead pixel clusters, color-banding gradients. The surface quality of a dying television signal or corrupted digital photograph. Analog noise meets digital destruction.\nCOMPOSITION: Subject fragmented across displaced horizontal bands. Multiple ghost-images offset in RGB channels. The composition itself is the corruption — order fighting entropy. Asymmetrical, unstable, anxiety-inducing framing.\nNEGATIVE: clean, pristine, high-resolution, smooth gradient, natural colors, warm lighting, oil painting, watercolor, pencil, traditional media, symmetrical, calm, organized."],
  ["neo_marble", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Hyper-realistic neoclassical white marble sculpture masterpiece. Polished Carrara marble with ornate architectural framing and breathtaking drapery. 8k resolution. --sref 650161255\nLIGHTING & VALUE: Soft, diffused museum lighting from above-left. Gentle shadow gradients across marble surfaces reveal subtle translucency in thin areas like ear lobes and fingertips. Warm ivory highlights on convex forms, cool blue-grey shadows in deep undercuts and fabric folds. The marble must appear to glow with absorbed light — luminous, not flat.\nCLARITY: Absolute sculptural precision. Every chisel mark refined to silk-smooth finish. Hair rendered as individual carved strands. Fabric folds flow with physical accuracy — weight, tension, and gravity all correct. Anatomical musculature visible beneath marble skin with Michelangelo-level authority.\nTEXTURE: Polished white Carrara marble — fine crystalline grain visible at close range, smooth as porcelain to the eye. Subtle grey veining running through the stone. The material must read unmistakably as stone — cold, heavy, permanent — yet the carved forms must feel impossibly alive.\nCOMPOSITION: Classical sculptural presentation — figures on architectural plinths, framed by ornate Corinthian columns and decorative relief panels. Dramatic contrapposto poses. Theatrical drapery cascading and billowing.\nNEGATIVE: color, paint, skin tone, warm flesh, digital, 2D, flat, illustration, cartoon, rough hewn, cracked, broken, modern, abstract, minimal."],
  ["xray_ghost", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Haunting translucent X-ray masterpiece. Ghostly, fragmented forms with visible skeletal and internal structures rendered in ethereal monochrome against deep black void. 8k resolution. --sref 3484196128\nLIGHTING & VALUE: Internal luminescence — subjects glow from within like deep-sea bioluminescence or backlit medical imaging. Cool blue-white spectral light reveals layered transparency: skin, muscle, bone, all simultaneously visible at different opacities. The darkest areas are absolute black void. The brightest areas are blown-out spectral white where dense structures block the internal light.\nCLARITY: Skeletal structures and internal anatomy rendered with medical-imaging precision. Web-like connective tissue networks visible as gossamer-fine translucent threads. The layered transparency must be coherent — near surfaces slightly opaque, deeper structures ghostly, deepest elements sharp and bright.\nTEXTURE: Spectral and immaterial. Surfaces feel like frosted glass, jellyfish membrane, or holographic projection. Fine web-like filaments and thread structures connect fragmented pieces. The subject should feel like it could dissolve into smoke at any moment — solid but barely.\nCOMPOSITION: Subjects isolated against deep black void. Fragmented and disjointed — pieces floating slightly separated, connected by translucent threads. The composition suggests forensic analysis or spiritual disembodiment.\nNEGATIVE: solid opaque surfaces, warm colors, skin texture, photorealistic flesh, cartoon, painterly, illustration, colorful, cheerful, heavy, grounded, earthy."],
  ["holo_iridescent", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Vibrant holographic iridescent 3D render masterpiece. Prismatic reflective surfaces shifting through the full spectrum with candy-chrome and soap-bubble optical qualities. 8k resolution. --sref 4100716776\nLIGHTING & VALUE: Multi-directional studio lighting designed to maximize iridescent color shifts. Every surface angle produces a different spectral color — hot magenta shifting to electric blue to acid green across a single curve. Specular highlights are pure white stars. Shadows are deep violet and indigo, never black. The entire image should shimmer with rainbow prismatic energy.\nCLARITY: Glass-smooth surface rendering with perfect specular reflections. Every color transition, every prismatic shift must be cleanly rendered with no banding or dithering. Bubble-like surface quality requires absolute precision in reflection mapping. Fine holographic interference patterns visible in flat surfaces.\nTEXTURE: Soap-bubble iridescence on chrome substrate. Oil-on-water color shifting. Candy-coated metallic automotive paint. The surface must feel simultaneously hard and ethereal. Some areas read as liquid, others as polished solid. Rainbow color gradients flow continuously across surfaces.\nCOMPOSITION: Playful, dynamic arrangements against white or soft pastel backgrounds. Floating objects, spheres, abstract shapes with bold graphic energy. The palette itself is the star — composition serves to maximize surface area for color display.\nNEGATIVE: matte, dull, monochrome, desaturated, earth tones, natural colors, rough texture, gritty, dark, gloomy, realistic skin, charcoal, pencil, ink, traditional media."],
  ["smoke_dissolve", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Dramatic black-and-white smoke-dissolve masterpiece. Subjects exploding into abstract smoky fragments and ink-cloud particles against stark white or deep black backgrounds. 8k resolution. --sref 3005544017\nLIGHTING & VALUE: Extreme high-contrast monochrome — pure black ink-smoke masses against paper-white void, or spectral white smoke wisps against pitch darkness. No middle greys in the transition zones — the boundary between solid form and smoke dissolution must be violent and abrupt. Where the subject is solid, it is intensely rendered. Where it dissolves, it becomes pure atmospheric chaos.\nCLARITY: Dual-state rendering — hyper-sharp photographic detail in the surviving solid areas of the subject, transitioning to soft, turbulent, fluid-dynamics smoke behavior in the dissolving areas. The boundary between solid and smoke must be visually electric — the exact moment of transformation.\nTEXTURE: Dense ink-in-water turbulence for smoke areas. Photographic skin/surface quality for solid areas. Fine particle scatter at dissolution edges — like ash caught in wind. The smoke must have real fluid-dynamics behavior: eddies, vortices, turbulent mixing layers.\nCOMPOSITION: Asymmetrical, explosive compositions. The subject partially destroyed — dissolving from one side, one limb, or fragmenting from center outward. Massive negative space where the dissolved material fades to nothing. The emotional weight is in what is being lost.\nNEGATIVE: color, gentle, soft gradients, smooth transitions, complete subjects, digital painting, cartoon, flat, illustrative, cheerful, warm tones, pastel, clean edges."],
  ["kintsugi", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Wabi-sabi kintsugi-inspired mixed-media masterpiece. Fragmented, cracked compositions with metallic gold veining and muted ink-wash grounds blending digital glitch with traditional aesthetics. 8k resolution. --sref 117215346\nLIGHTING & VALUE: Muted, desaturated base tones — ash grey, bone white, charcoal black — punctuated by luminous metallic gold and warm amber accents in the fracture lines. The gold should feel like it is emitting its own warm light from within the cracks. Overall mood is overcast and melancholic, with the gold providing moments of radiant beauty within the damage.\nCLARITY: Dual-quality rendering — areas of photographic clarity adjacent to areas of intentional blur, grain, and fragmentation. The cracks and gold veining must be sharp and precise. The surrounding image can be degraded, torn, or glitched. The contrast between broken surface and precious repair IS the visual statement.\nTEXTURE: Mixed-media layering — ink wash, torn paper edges, photographic fragments, metallic leaf application, digital pixel artifacts. The surface should feel like a collaged assemblage of incompatible materials unified by the gold fracture network. Visible paper grain, metallic foil texture, and digital compression blocks coexisting.\nCOMPOSITION: Fragmented and reassembled. The image is broken into irregular pieces — some shifted, some missing — with luminous gold filling the gaps like molten precious metal poured into wounds. Nature motifs emerging from abstract destruction.\nNEGATIVE: pristine, clean, perfect, unbroken, digital polish, smooth gradients, bright saturated colors, cartoon, vector, cheerful, modern minimalist, plastic, uniform texture."],
  ["biomech_surreal", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Biomechanical surrealist concept art. Angular interlocking organic-machine hybrid forms with a restricted palette of warm cream, charcoal black, and blood red. Clean digital painting with deliberate, readable shapes. --sref 3330408347\nLIGHTING & VALUE: Flat-to-moderate directional light. Shadows define form but stay clean — no noisy gradients. High contrast between the red accent elements and the desaturated bone/grey base. Forms read as bold silhouettes first, detail second.\nCLARITY: Mid-level detail — enough to define mechanical joints, organic membranes, and structural connections, but never so much that the design becomes noisy. Every element must read clearly at arm's length. Shapes are decisive and intentional.\nTEXTURE: Smooth matte surfaces. No heavy rendering, no painterly brushwork. Clean like concept art or a screen print. Slight paper grain is acceptable but the forms themselves are crisp and graphic.\nCOMPOSITION: Dynamic asymmetrical arrangements with clear figure-ground separation. Subject isolated or set against minimal atmospheric backgrounds. Figures interact with mechanical extensions and biomorphic structures as one unified design.\nNEGATIVE: photorealistic, hyper-detailed, noisy textures, busy backgrounds, soft focus, watercolor, sketchy, pencil, fine-line, engraving, hatching, anime, cute."],
  ["retro_cosmic", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Retro-futuristic cosmic poster art. Bold geometric compositions with neon orange and teal against deep space-black backgrounds. Clean vector-like shapes with architectural precision. --sref 1878163327\nLIGHTING & VALUE: Glowing neon-warm elements (orange, amber, gold) against cold dark backgrounds (deep teal, midnight blue, black). Light sources are geometric — concentric rings, radiating lines, orbital arcs. The glow is the design. Flat value blocks with minimal gradation keep everything graphic and readable.\nCLARITY: Clean, graphic, poster-level readability. Shapes are geometric and precise — circles, arcs, chevrons, horizon lines. No fuzzy edges, no atmospheric haze. Every element is intentional and could be cut from vinyl.\nTEXTURE: Smooth and flat. The quality of a high-end screen print or risograph. No visible brushwork, no grain unless as a deliberate halftone overlay. Surfaces are matte and clean.\nCOMPOSITION: Symmetrical or strongly centered compositions. Monumental scale — tiny figures against vast cosmic architecture. Concentric circular motifs, radiating line systems, strong horizon lines. The composition itself is the design pattern.\nNEGATIVE: photorealistic, painterly, loose brushwork, sketchy, watercolor, organic shapes, messy, noisy, cluttered, earth tones, pastel, soft lighting, fine detail, engraving."],
  ["urban_pop", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Bold urban pop art meets macabre surrealism. Flat color screen-print aesthetic with heavy black outlines, vibrant limited palette, and tribal-graphic mask-like faces. --sref 2353910454\nLIGHTING & VALUE: Flat, graphic, no traditional lighting. Value is created through color blocks and solid black shapes, not gradients. High contrast between saturated color areas and heavy black line masses. The style is closer to printmaking than painting — every tone is a distinct flat layer.\nCLARITY: Maximum graphic clarity. Every shape is defined by a bold black outline or a hard color edge. No blending, no soft transitions. Forms are simplified and stylized — readable instantly like street signage or protest posters.\nTEXTURE: Screen-print quality. Flat matte ink on paper. Visible registration overlap where color layers meet. Slight texture from the printing process but the shapes themselves are clean and bold. No digital smoothness — it should feel hand-pulled.\nCOMPOSITION: Dense, dynamic arrangements that fill the frame. Horror vacui energy — the composition is packed but every element is a clean, readable shape. Figures, skulls, botanical elements, and geometric patterns interlocking like a puzzle.\nNEGATIVE: photorealistic, soft shading, gradients, 3D rendering, fine detail, smooth digital art, watercolor, pencil, subtle, minimal, muted colors, engraving, hatching."],
  ["contour_line", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Abstract contour-line sculpture. Flowing topographic line systems that define organic, morphing human and abstract forms. Monochromatic black lines on white ground. --sref 1605091586\nLIGHTING & VALUE: No traditional lighting. Value and volume are constructed entirely through line density and spacing — tighter lines read as shadow, wider spacing reads as highlight. The forms appear three-dimensional through the contour system alone. Pure graphic logic, no shading fills.\nCLARITY: Clean, precise, evenly weighted lines. Each contour line must be individually traceable as it wraps around the form. The line system must be consistent and rhythmic — no scratchy or broken lines. The simplicity IS the sophistication.\nTEXTURE: Smooth, precise, mechanical line quality. The feel of a CNC-plotted pen drawing or a 3D wireframe render printed on paper. No hand-drawn wobble. Clean, mathematical, meditative. White paper ground, black ink lines.\nCOMPOSITION: Single subject centered or slightly off-center against clean white background. The contour lines extend slightly beyond the form's boundary, suggesting movement or dissolution. Generous negative space. The design breathes.\nNEGATIVE: filled shading, solid black areas, color, painterly, rough sketch, hatching, crosshatch, busy backgrounds, multiple subjects, photorealistic, noisy, textured surfaces, detailed, cluttered."],
  ["psych_flow", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Bold psychedelic flow art. Smooth, undulating biomorphic shapes with saturated hot palette — electric orange, magenta, deep violet, molten red — and strong symmetrical compositions. Clean, not noisy. --sref 2122985629\nLIGHTING & VALUE: No realistic lighting. Color IS light. The brightest, most saturated areas pull forward while darker tones recede. Smooth gradient transitions between color zones create a liquid, flowing sense of depth. No hard shadows, no spotlights — just pure color energy radiating outward.\nCLARITY: Smooth, clean curves and flowing shapes. No rough edges, no noise, no texture. Every undulating form has a crisp, defined boundary. The complexity comes from the layered flowing forms, not from surface detail. It should feel like looking into a lava lamp or liquid light show.\nTEXTURE: Glass-smooth. Zero surface texture. The quality of a high-resolution vector render or backlit transparency. Colors blend through smooth gradients only — no grain, no stipple, no halftone. Surfaces are impossibly clean and luminous.\nCOMPOSITION: Symmetrical or near-symmetrical. Radial flow patterns emanating from center. Figures emerging from or dissolving into flowing color waves. The composition should feel like a mandala in motion — organized but alive.\nNEGATIVE: rough texture, gritty, noisy, muted colors, earth tones, realistic lighting, hard shadows, angular shapes, geometric, sketch, pencil, monochrome, fine detail, engraving, hatching."],
  ["stained_glass", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Stained glass cubist composition. Bold dark lead-line outlines divide the image into jewel-toned color panels with Art Deco geometric structure. Flat color fills within each glass segment. --sref 250379662\nLIGHTING & VALUE: Backlit luminosity — every color panel glows as if sunlight is passing through tinted glass from behind. Jewel tones: emerald green, sapphire blue, amber gold, ruby red. The dark lead lines create a strong graphic skeleton. No cast shadows — the light is ambient and comes through the glass itself.\nCLARITY: Clean geometric panel divisions with bold dark outlines. Each color segment has a flat or near-flat fill. The lead-line framework must be consistent in weight and clearly define every shape. The overall composition reads as a unified design even when zoomed into individual panels.\nTEXTURE: Smooth glass-like color fills. Subtle translucency variation within panels is acceptable but no heavy texture. The dark outlines should feel like wrought iron or lead came — consistent, structural, bold. The overall quality of an Art Deco window or Tiffany panel.\nCOMPOSITION: Structured, architectural framing. Subjects are fragmented across panels like a cubist portrait seen through a cathedral window. Strong vertical and diagonal lead lines create rhythm. Decorative border elements frame the central design.\nNEGATIVE: photorealistic, soft blending, no outlines, watercolor, pencil, gradient fills, 3D rendering, smooth transitions, engraving, fine detail, busy, noisy, monochrome."],
  ["trash_polka", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Aggressive trash polka expressionist collage. Strictly black, white, and blood-red palette. Bold gestural brushstrokes, torn-edge fragments, and chaotic energy channeled through a three-color restriction. --sref 852747055\nLIGHTING & VALUE: No naturalistic lighting. Pure graphic contrast — violent black masses, raw white negative space, and strategic red accent strikes. The red hits like alarm signals against the monochrome chaos. Value is created through the collision of opaque black strokes and exposed white ground.\nCLARITY: Intentionally raw but readable. Individual brushstrokes must be bold and decisive — not blurred or mushy. The chaos is structured — every slash, splatter, and torn edge contributes to the overall composition. Forms are suggested through gesture, not outlined precisely.\nTEXTURE: Aggressive mixed-media surface. Visible brushstroke direction, palette-knife scrapes, torn paper edges, and ink splatter. The quality of a punk concert poster printed on cheap stock — raw, physical, unapologetic. No digital smoothness.\nCOMPOSITION: Explosive asymmetrical compositions. Collage logic — overlapping fragments, rotated elements, scale jumps. A photographic face might collide with a calligraphic slash and a geometric red block. The composition should feel like controlled demolition.\nNEGATIVE: clean, precise, smooth, symmetrical, digital polish, pastels, soft colors, gradients, photorealistic, fine-line, delicate, engraving, cute, minimal, elegant, refined."],
  ["double_exp", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Cinematic double-exposure composite. Human silhouettes filled with atmospheric landscape imagery — forests, mountains, ocean, sky. Muted, cool-toned palette with warm accent highlights. Dreamlike and contemplative. --sref 3116065170\nLIGHTING & VALUE: Soft, diffused, cinematic. The silhouette subject is defined by the boundary between the internal landscape and the external background. Muted blue-grey base tones with isolated warm highlights (sunset amber, golden hour glow). The brightest values sit within the silhouette where sky meets treeline. Low overall contrast — moody and atmospheric.\nCLARITY: The silhouette edge must be clean and recognizable — the subject's outline is the primary design element. Interior landscape imagery is soft and atmospheric, not sharp or detailed. The blend between portrait and landscape should feel seamless and organic. No hard composite edges.\nTEXTURE: Photographic grain — the quality of analog film double exposure. Soft focus on landscape elements inside the silhouette. The overall surface should feel like a slightly faded photograph — not digital-crisp. Mist, fog, and atmospheric haze soften interior details.\nCOMPOSITION: Single-figure silhouette (head/bust or full body) containing a layered landscape. Clean background — solid color, gradient, or minimal environment. Strong profile or three-quarter silhouette reads instantly. The interior landscape has its own horizon line and depth.\nNEGATIVE: harsh contrast, sharp detail, bright saturated colors, cartoon, illustration, multiple exposures, busy, cluttered, abstract, geometric, bold outlines, engraving, graphic, flat."],
  ["delft_blue", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Dutch Delft blue-and-white porcelain tile art. Bold cobalt blue graphic silhouettes and botanical patterns on clean cream-white ground. Flat, decorative, and inherently design-ready. --sref 456269934\nLIGHTING & VALUE: No dimensional lighting. Pure two-tone graphic system — solid cobalt blue shapes on white ground. Value range is restricted: dense blue for dark areas, white ground for light, and occasional mid-blue washes for accent depth. The flatness is intentional and beautiful.\nCLARITY: Clean, decisive silhouette edges. Every leaf, figure, and architectural element is defined by a crisp blue-on-white boundary. Decorative pattern elements (florals, scrollwork, borders) are precise and evenly weighted. The design should look like it could be painted on a ceramic plate or tile.\nTEXTURE: Smooth porcelain surface quality. Flat matte blue pigment on glazed white. Very slight hand-painted variation in blue density is acceptable — it adds warmth without chaos. No heavy texture, no visible brushwork, no grain. Clean, refined, ceramic.\nCOMPOSITION: Balanced, decorative arrangements. Figures framed by botanical border elements — flowering vines, leaf scrollwork, decorative tile patterns. Symmetrical tendencies. The composition should feel like a complete design object — a plate, a tile panel, a decorative vignette.\nNEGATIVE: multicolor, realistic shading, gradients, 3D rendering, modern, digital, neon, dark backgrounds, gritty, rough, abstract, minimal, photorealistic, engraving, fine-line."],
  ["graphic_occult", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Bold graphic occult poster art. Dark monochromatic base with strategic deep-red accents. Clean symmetrical compositions with esoteric symbolism, bold shapes, and ritual energy. Closer to vector design than painting. --sref 4018681715\nLIGHTING & VALUE: Flat graphic lighting. Dominant solid blacks and warm cream/bone whites with surgical red accent placement. No gradients, no atmospheric effects. Every value is a clean, printable tone. The black areas are confident and heavy. The cream areas breathe. The red areas command attention.\nCLARITY: Maximum graphic readability. Bold, clean shapes that work at any scale — from a phone screen to a wall poster. Strong symmetrical structures. Iconographic simplicity — skulls, eyes, celestial bodies, geometric frames are reduced to their most powerful graphic form. No unnecessary detail.\nTEXTURE: Clean matte print quality. Flat ink on heavy cream stock. The precision of vector art with the warmth of letterpress printing. No visible brushwork, no painterly effects. Some deliberate distress texture adds character without reducing clarity.\nCOMPOSITION: Strict bilateral symmetry. Central iconic figure or symbol framed by geometric borders, radiating lines, or celestial arcs. Tarot card and concert poster composition logic. The design is self-contained — it works as a standalone graphic object with built-in framing.\nNEGATIVE: photorealistic, soft, subtle, pastel colors, gradients, 3D rendering, painterly, watercolor, loose brushwork, asymmetrical chaos, fine-line detail, engraving, anime, cute."],
  ["cinematic_portrait", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Museum-grade graphite realism on heavyweight cotton rag. Photographic fidelity rendered entirely in pencil and compressed charcoal. 8k resolution. LIGHTING & VALUE: Cinematic Rembrandt lighting with a single dominant light source. Shadows carved in layered 8B graphite — dense, velvet-black, and burnished to a metallic sheen. Highlights are raw paper white, untouched, creating the illusion of wet light on skin. The tonal range must span 11 stops from pure white to absolute black. SKIN: Render every pore, every micro-wrinkle, every follicle. Subsurface scattering implied through soft gradient transitions in midtones. Oily sheen on nose, forehead, and lips. HAIR: Individual strand rendering with directional flow. Flyaways catching backlight as thin white lines against dark mass. HANDS & DETAILS: Anatomically precise with visible tendons, knuckle creases, and nail texture. Jewelry rendered with hard specular reflections. PAPER: Visible cold-press cotton tooth beneath the graphite. COMPOSITION: Tight crop, subject isolated against clean off-white negative space with subtle vignette falloff. NEGATIVE: blurry, smudged, airbrushed, digital painting, soft focus, flat lighting, muddy midtones, cartoon, anime, vector, watercolor wash, colored."],
  ["raw_street_portrait", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Raw graphite photorealism. Executed in 2H through 9B pencil range on cold-press illustration board. 8k resolution. The drawing should be indistinguishable from a black-and-white large-format photograph at first glance. LIGHTING & VALUE: Harsh directional overhead or side light creating deep eye socket shadows and hard-edge cast shadows. No fill light. Blacks are absolute — compressed charcoal burnished into the paper grain until no tooth is visible. Whites are bare paper, sharp and clean. TEXTURE PRIORITY: This is a texture study. Render fabric weave, leather grain, metal patina, concrete dust, tattoo ink density differences between fresh and healed work. Skin shows environmental wear — sun damage, stubble shadow, expression lines rendered at pore-level. EDGES: Mix of razor-sharp contour edges where light meets shadow and lost edges where form dissolves into background. COMPOSITION: Subject anchored in upper portion, body dissolving into raw paper below — an unfinished-edge treatment where photorealism gradually becomes visible pencil strokes then bare paper. NEGATIVE: smooth, airbrushed, soft, glamour lighting, fill flash, digital, painted, blurry, low resolution, uniform shading."],
  ["intimate_detail", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Technical graphite illustration meets fine art portraiture. Executed with mechanical pencil (0.3mm lead) and powdered graphite on hot-press Bristol. 8k resolution with macro-photography sharpness. LIGHTING & VALUE: Soft but directional beauty lighting — minimal shadow, maximum detail visibility. The tonal approach favors a full midtone range with surgical highlight placement. White highlights are small, precise, and placed only on the wettest or most reflective surfaces: eyes, lips, jewelry, sweat. Shadows are transparent — built through cross-hatching visible only at extreme zoom. DETAIL MANDATE: This is a forensic-level render. Iris fibers and blood vessels in eyes. Lip texture showing individual vertical ridges. Piercing holes showing skin tension. Eyelash roots visible at the lash line. Pore-level skin rendering with visible sebaceous detail. JEWELRY & ACCESSORIES: Hard metallic rendering — chrome-level reflections with geometric highlight shapes. Pearl iridescence through careful value gradients. COMPOSITION: Extreme crop emphasizing face and hands. Clean negative space. No background elements. NEGATIVE: blurry, out of focus, painterly, impressionistic, loose strokes, smudged, soft, digital filter, AI-smooth skin, flat, low contrast."],
  ["high_fashion_editorial", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: High-fashion graphite editorial. The precision of Irving Penn's platinum prints translated into hand-drawn graphite and charcoal on archival cotton paper. 8k resolution. LIGHTING & VALUE: Extreme high-key with aggressive shadow falloff. Shadows are carved — not gradual but almost binary in their transition, creating a graphic, fashion-editorial quality. The deepest blacks should read as liquid ink. Highlights are blown-out bare paper white across large skin areas, creating an almost overexposed luminosity. Midtones are minimal and reserved for turning-form transitions. SKIN RENDERING: Porcelain-smooth in highlight areas with sudden, detailed texture appearing only in shadow zones — this contrast between smooth light and textured shadow creates the \"magazine\" quality. HAIR: Treated as a sculptural mass — deep black with individual strands visible only at the edges where hair meets light. FABRIC & MATERIAL: If clothing is present, render material with obsessive accuracy — silk drape, leather compression, lace transparency. COMPOSITION: Fashion pose. Strong diagonal energy. Subject isolated on pristine off-white paper. Generous negative space suggesting a gallery or editorial print. NEGATIVE: muddy, grey, flat, soft, casual, snapshot quality, blurry, digital, painted, warm tones, sepia, colored, low resolution, smudged."],
  ["anatomical_tension", "[SUBJECT]. STYLE: Anatomical graphite masterwork in the tradition of classical atelier drawing elevated to photographic hyperrealism. 8k resolution. Executed in graphite pencil (full range), compressed charcoal, and eraser-lift techniques on heavyweight vellum-finish paper. LIGHTING & VALUE: Raking side light that emphasizes surface topology — every tendon, vein, and muscle insertion is revealed through shadow. Extreme chiaroscuro with lost-and-found edges. Darkest values achieved through multiple burnished charcoal layers. Lightest values are subtractive — lifted from toned ground with kneaded eraser for a luminous, almost glowing quality. ANATOMICAL FOCUS: Hands rendered with surgical precision — visible metacarpal structure, tendon tracking, nail lunula, cuticle detail, fingerprint whorls. Body landmarks (clavicle, scapula, ribcage, hip bone) must read clearly through skin. Muscle fibers implied through directional shading strokes. SURFACE: Visible sweat, goosebumps, body hair rendered as individual strands. Tattoos (if present) rendered with ink-density accuracy showing how ink sits differently in different skin layers. COMPOSITION: Dynamic pose with hands as co-focal point. Body emerging from and dissolving into the paper — controlled unfinished edges. Clean paper background. NEGATIVE: stiff, posed, flat, soft, blurry, airbrushed, digital, painted, smooth plastic skin, anatomically incorrect, cartoon, low detail."],
  ["biomech_chrome_couture", "[SUBJECT]. RESTYLE ONLY — do not add, remove, or alter any elements of the original subject. No new objects, accessories, clothing, or anatomy. Preserve the exact composition, pose, and silhouette. STYLE: Biomechanical chrome rendering applied to the existing subject only. Sorayama chrome surface treatment over original forms. 8k resolution rendered for bold clarity — every shape must read cleanly at arm's length. SURFACE & MATERIAL: Re-render all existing surfaces as liquid rose-gold chrome using smooth, unbroken tonal gradients — no stippling, no crosshatching, no fine texture. Chrome reflections are simplified into broad curved bands of light-to-dark. Transitions between values are buttery smooth airbrush-quality gradients. FORM TREATMENT: Existing edges and contours of the subject become aerodynamic and swept-back. Original shapes are stylized as chrome panels with clean borders — but the shapes themselves remain faithful to the source. No new mechanical parts, no added spines, no added armor, no added appendages. LIGHTING: Soft diffused studio light. Shadows are smooth gradients into deep black. Specular highlights are large, bold, white hotspots on convex surfaces. COLOR PALETTE: Rose gold, warm chrome, blush pink, deep black, crimson red only. Maximum 4-5 distinct tonal values across any surface. COMPOSITION: Maintain original composition exactly. Clean off-white background. Generous negative space. NEGATIVE: added elements, new accessories, chains, jewelry, ribbons, bows, glasses, sunglasses, spikes, weapons, wings, extra limbs, clothing not in original, fine lines, stippling, crosshatching, intricate mechanical details, small text, thin lines, busy patterns, complex textures, noisy gradients, dithering, dotwork, fine filigree."],
  ["kawaii_chrome_blob", "[SUBJECT]. RESTYLE ONLY — do not add, remove, or alter any elements of the original subject. No new objects, accessories, or features. Preserve the exact composition and subject identity. STYLE: Kawaii chrome sculpture treatment — the existing subject is re-rendered as simplified, inflated, precious chrome. 8k resolution with bold smooth forms. SURFACE & MATERIAL: Re-render all existing surfaces as flawless pearl-to-rose-gold chrome. Inflate and round the original forms while keeping the subject recognizable. Surface reflections rendered as 3-4 broad, smooth gradient bands — one highlight zone, one midtone, one shadow crescent. No complex environmental reflections. Each gradient transition is wide and seamless, like airbrushed automotive paint. SIMPLIFICATION RULE: Simplify the original subject's forms into bold rounded shapes. Reduce detail, do not add detail. If any feature is smaller than a pea at render scale, smooth it away. The charm comes from simplifying what exists, not from adding new elements. EYES (if present in original): Enlarge and simplify existing eyes — deep glassy black-to-cosmic-purple with 2-3 large bold star-shaped specular highlights. LIGHTING: Ultra-soft omnidirectional. Reflective plane below creating a single clean mirror reflection. 2-4 four-pointed star sparkles as graphic accents only. COLOR PALETTE: Pearl white, blush pink, rose gold, deep cosmic purple-black. All pastels. COMPOSITION: Maintain original subject placement. Soft gradient background. Maximum negative space. NEGATIVE: added elements, new accessories, chains, bows, ribbons, glasses, hats, clothing not in original, weapons, wings, fine detail, complex reflections, scattered sparkles, stippling, crosshatching, busy patterns, intricate textures, thin lines, noisy gradients."],
  ["dark_botanical_specimen", "[SUBJECT]. RESTYLE ONLY — do not add, remove, or alter any elements of the original subject. No new objects, flowers, leaves, chains, beads, jewelry, or ornaments unless they exist in the original. Preserve the exact composition and silhouette. STYLE: Gothic botanical rendering on black — Victorian specimen plate meets modern blackwork tattoo. 8k resolution with bold, clean rendering. BACKGROUND: Pure velvety matte black. Subject floats in void. RENDERING TECHNIQUE: Re-render the existing subject in white and grey on black — as if drawn with white pencil and grey wash on black paper with SMOOTH gradients. All existing forms rendered in broad silvery-white tonal bands. Any line structures are single clean bold white lines — not hairline-thin. Each surface reads as 3-4 smooth value zones (bright edge highlight, mid-grey body, dark shadow crescent). SELECTIVE COLOR: One existing focal element rendered in smooth pink-to-crimson gradient — blended seamlessly like soft watercolor wash. Green permitted only where naturally appropriate as a secondary accent, also smooth gradient. SHAPE HIERARCHY: 3 clear value layers within the existing subject's forms so they separate cleanly. No new decorative elements added to achieve this hierarchy. COMPOSITION: Maintain original subject placement. Floating in black void. NEGATIVE: added elements, chains, beads, pendants, jewelry, ornaments, ribbons, bows, accessories not in original, fine stippling, dotwork, crosshatching, hairline details, busy patterns, realistic texture, visible paper grain, thin botanical linework, noisy gradients, scattered small elements."],
  ["y2k_gothic_chrome", "[SUBJECT]. RESTYLE ONLY — do not add, remove, or alter any elements of the original subject. No new objects, accessories, chains, bows, ribbons, spikes, glasses, sunglasses, or jewelry. Preserve the exact composition, pose, and silhouette faithfully. STYLE: Y2K gothic chrome rendering — early-2000s visual kei aesthetic applied as a surface treatment only. 8k resolution with bold graphic clarity. SURFACE & MATERIAL: Re-render all existing surfaces as polished liquid chrome — cool-toned silver. Every existing form becomes mirror-bright but with SIMPLIFIED reflections: each chrome surface gets one dominant highlight stripe, one large shadow mass, one midtone zone. The chrome reads as 3 clean value bands per surface — white, grey, black — with smooth transitions. CONTRAST: High-contrast graphic rendering. Shadows are near-black. Highlights are pure white. All transitions are SMOOTH gradients — chrome airbrush quality. FORM TREATMENT: Existing forms are stylized with bold graphic clarity. Original shapes are re-rendered with chunky, readable chrome surfaces. Simplify existing details into fewer, bolder planes — do not add new forms or accessories. BACKGROUND: Flat medium-dark grey. No gradient, no environment. COMPOSITION: Maintain original composition exactly. Every existing element remains separable — clean visual hierarchy of the original subject. NEGATIVE: added elements, chains, bows, ribbons, spikes, glasses, sunglasses, jewelry, accessories not in original, clothing not in original, wings, weapons, fine detail, intricate mechanics, complex reflections, thin lines, small ornaments, busy patterns, textured surfaces, warm tones, gold, copper, stippling, dotwork."],
  ["porcelain_chrome", "[SUBJECT].\nRESTYLE ONLY — do not add, remove, or alter any elements of the original subject. No new objects, accessories, clothing, or anatomy. Preserve exact composition, pose, and silhouette.\nSTYLE: Porcelain chrome rendering applied to the existing subject only. 8k clarity with bold readable forms.\nSURFACE & MATERIAL: Re-render all existing surfaces as lustrous porcelain chrome with a cool silver-white base and delicate thin blue veining that follows existing contours. Reflections are simplified into broad curved light-to-dark bands with creamy airbrushed transitions. No stippling, crosshatching, grit, or noisy texture.\nFORM TREATMENT: Existing edges remain faithful to source anatomy and structure, with polished ceramic smoothness. Subject appears dipped in liquid porcelain chrome without new mechanical parts or appendages.\nLIGHTING: Soft diffused overhead light. Smooth cool-grey shadow gradients. Large white hotspot highlights with subtle blue secondary reflections.\nCOLOR PALETTE: Silver-white, cool blue veining, pearl grey, warm gold accent notes, deep charcoal. Maximum 4-5 tonal values per surface.\nCOMPOSITION: Maintain original composition exactly. Clean off-white background. Generous negative space. No ground-plane cast shadow.\nNEGATIVE: added elements, new accessories, chains, jewelry, ribbons, bows, glasses, sunglasses, spikes, weapons, wings, extra limbs, clothing not in original, fine lines, stippling, crosshatching, intricate mechanics, small text, thin lines, busy patterns, complex textures, noisy gradients, dithering, dotwork, fine filigree."],
  ["biomech_red_core", "[SUBJECT].\nRESTYLE ONLY — do not add, remove, or alter any elements of the original subject. No new objects, accessories, clothing, or anatomy. Preserve exact composition, pose, and silhouette.\nSTYLE: Biomechanical chrome rendering applied to existing subject only. 8k clarity with dramatic readability.\nSURFACE & MATERIAL: Re-render all existing surfaces as polished semi-translucent liquid chrome with deep crimson interior luminance visible through seams and thinner regions. Chrome reflections are sharp and high-contrast. Transitions between metal shell and inner glow are clean and deliberate.\nFORM TREATMENT: Existing forms become sleek biomechanical paneling while preserving original structure. No added armor pieces, spines, appendages, or extra machinery.\nLIGHTING: Cinematic top light with strong contrast. Deep black shadows. Razor white specular hotspots. Interior red glow acts as secondary fill from within.\nCOLOR PALETTE: Polished silver chrome, deep crimson red glow, jet black, warm white highlights only. Maximum 4-5 tonal values per surface.\nCOMPOSITION: Maintain original composition exactly. Clean white background. Generous negative space.\nNEGATIVE: added elements, new accessories, chains, jewelry, ribbons, bows, glasses, sunglasses, spikes, weapons, wings, extra limbs, clothing not in original, fine lines, stippling, crosshatching, small text, busy patterns, complex textures, noisy gradients, dithering, dotwork, filigree."],
  ["dripping_chrome", "[SUBJECT].\nRESTYLE ONLY — do not add, remove, or alter any elements of the original subject. Preserve exact composition, pose, and silhouette.\nSTYLE: Hyper-realistic dripping liquid chrome rendering over existing forms only. 8k clarity with strong silhouette readability.\nSURFACE & MATERIAL: Re-render all existing surfaces as ultra-polished liquid chrome, with viscous metal drips extending downward from naturally low points. Keep smooth unbroken tonal gradients and dramatic reflective bands. No stippling, crosshatching, or grain.\nFORM TREATMENT: Core silhouette remains faithful. Edge regions soften into gravity-driven chrome drips without introducing unrelated shapes or objects.\nLIGHTING: Cinematic studio lighting with high contrast. Sharp white specular highlights on convex chrome and individual drips. Deep black and gunmetal shadow bands.\nCOLOR PALETTE: Neutral silver chrome, gunmetal grey, deep black, bright white highlights only. Maximum 4-5 tonal values per surface.\nCOMPOSITION: Maintain original composition exactly. Clean white background. Generous negative space.\nNEGATIVE: added objects, new accessories, chains, jewelry, ribbons, bows, glasses, spikes, weapons, wings, extra limbs, clothing not in original, fine-line detail clutter, stippling, crosshatching, intricate mechanics, small text, busy patterns, noisy gradients, dithering, dotwork."],
  ["honey_gold_chrome", "[SUBJECT].\nRESTYLE ONLY — do not add, remove, or alter any elements of the original subject. Preserve exact composition, pose, and silhouette.\nSTYLE: Golden honey chrome rendering applied to existing subject only. 8k bold clarity.\nSURFACE & MATERIAL: Re-render all existing surfaces as warm liquid gold chrome with honey-thick viscosity. Reflections are rich amber-to-brown tonal sweeps with buttery smooth gradients. Natural drip behavior appears only at low points of existing forms.\nFORM TREATMENT: Existing edges and contours remain faithful while gaining viscous golden chrome flow. No new parts, appendages, or accessories.\nLIGHTING: Warm studio light from upper-left. Smooth shadow transitions into deep amber-brown. Large warm-white hotspot highlights.\nCOLOR PALETTE: Rich gold, warm amber, honey brown, deep brown-black, warm white highlights only. Maximum 4-5 tonal values.\nCOMPOSITION: Maintain original composition exactly. Clean off-white background. Generous negative space.\nNEGATIVE: added elements, new accessories, jewelry, ribbons, bows, glasses, spikes, weapons, wings, extra limbs, clothing not in original, fine lines, stippling, crosshatching, intricate mechanics, small text, busy patterns, complex textures, noisy gradients, dithering, dotwork."],
  ["chrome_portal_frame", "[SUBJECT].\nRESTYLE ONLY — do not add, remove, or alter subject matter. Preserve original composition, pose, and silhouette.\nSTYLE: Chrome melting-edge portal frame treatment derived from the subject's existing boundary only. 8k clarity.\nSURFACE & MATERIAL: Re-render the periphery of existing forms as liquid chrome with melting, dripping edge behavior. Chrome is high-contrast polished silver with broad smooth gradients. Interior forms remain faithful while outer edges dissolve into molten chrome.\nFORM TREATMENT: Effect is constrained to existing contour boundary. No separate frame object, no new ornaments, no additional accessories.\nLIGHTING: Soft diffused studio lighting. Smooth gradients into deep black shadows. Large white hotspot highlights on convex chrome border regions.\nCOLOR PALETTE: Polished silver, cool grey, deep black, bright white highlights only. Maximum 4-5 tonal values.\nCOMPOSITION: Maintain original composition exactly. Clean off-white background. Generous negative space.\nNEGATIVE: added objects, new accessories, separate decorative frames, chains, ribbons, bows, glasses, spikes, weapons, wings, extra limbs, fine stippling, crosshatching, intricate mechanics, small text, busy texture fields, dithering, dotwork."],
  ["bw_micro_chrome", "[SUBJECT].\nRESTYLE ONLY — do not add, remove, or alter any elements of the original subject. Preserve exact composition, pose, and silhouette.\nSTYLE: Realistic shiny chrome silver microrealism with fine-line tattoo presentation. 8k bold clarity.\nSURFACE & MATERIAL: Re-render all existing surfaces as polished silver chrome using only black, white, and neutral grey. Reflections are simplified into dramatic tonal bands with smooth airbrushed transitions. No stippling, crosshatching, grit, or color.\nFORM TREATMENT: Existing forms remain faithful with crisp contour integrity. No new parts or accessories.\nLIGHTING: High-contrast directional studio light. Deep black shadows and bright white specular hotspots.\nCOLOR PALETTE: Silver chrome, pure white, pure black, neutral grey only. Maximum 4-5 tonal values.\nCOMPOSITION: Maintain original composition exactly. Clean white background. Generous negative space.\nNEGATIVE: added elements, new accessories, color, chains, jewelry, ribbons, bows, glasses, spikes, weapons, wings, extra limbs, clothing not in original, stippling, crosshatching, intricate mechanics, small text, busy patterns, noisy gradients, dithering, dotwork."],
  ["prismatic_chrome", "[SUBJECT].\nRESTYLE ONLY — do not add, remove, or alter any elements of the original subject. Preserve exact composition, pose, and silhouette.\nSTYLE: Colorful prismatic chrome rendering applied to existing subject only. 8k clarity.\nSURFACE & MATERIAL: Re-render all existing surfaces as polished chrome with oil-slick prismatic spectral shifts across curvature. Maintain mirror-smooth gradients and bold readable reflections. No stippling, crosshatching, or gritty texture.\nFORM TREATMENT: Existing contours remain faithful; only surface material changes to prismatic chrome.\nLIGHTING: Soft diffused studio light to emphasize spectral shifts. Smooth deep-charcoal shadow gradients. Large white highlights that bloom into prismatic fringes.\nCOLOR PALETTE: Electric blue, magenta, emerald, gold, violet over chrome base, with deep black shadows and bright white highlights.\nCOMPOSITION: Maintain original composition exactly. Clean white background. Generous negative space.\nNEGATIVE: added elements, new accessories, chains, jewelry, ribbons, bows, glasses, spikes, weapons, wings, extra limbs, clothing not in original, fine lines, stippling, crosshatching, intricate mechanics, small text, busy patterns, noisy gradients, dithering, dotwork."],
  ["mirror_chrome_ornate", "[SUBJECT].\nRESTYLE ONLY — do not add, remove, or alter any elements of the original subject. Preserve exact composition, pose, and silhouette.\nSTYLE: Lustrous mirror chrome rendering with ornate high-contrast reflection behavior. 8k clarity.\nSURFACE & MATERIAL: Re-render all existing surfaces as perfect mirror silver chrome with warped abstract environmental reflections. Keep radiant glistening highlights and broad silver value bands. No matte patches, stippling, or crosshatching.\nFORM TREATMENT: Preserve existing edges and structure with sculptural chrome fidelity. No new parts or accessories.\nLIGHTING: Dramatic contrast lighting against a dark field. Rich blacks and vivid white mirror flashes on convex surfaces.\nCOLOR PALETTE: Lustrous silver, brilliant white, deep jet black, warm grey midtones only. Maximum 4-5 tonal values.\nCOMPOSITION: Maintain original composition exactly. Clean black background. Generous dramatic negative space.\nNEGATIVE: added elements, new accessories, chains, jewelry, ribbons, bows, glasses, spikes, weapons, wings, extra limbs, clothing not in original, fine-line clutter, stippling, crosshatching, small text, busy textures, noisy gradients, dithering, dotwork."],
  ["dore_chrome_line", "[SUBJECT].\nRESTYLE ONLY — do not add, remove, or alter any elements of the original subject. Preserve exact composition, pose, and silhouette.\nSTYLE: Chrome fine-line engraving illustration in a Gustave Dore-inspired approach. 8k clarity.\nSURFACE & MATERIAL: Re-render all existing surfaces as chrome metal expressed through dense-to-sparse line engraving. Chrome reflections are described by line direction and line density, not soft blur. Keep clean single-stroke line behavior and rich blacks.\nFORM TREATMENT: Existing contours remain faithful and are articulated through precise line structure. No new parts or accessories.\nLIGHTING: Dramatic low-angle contrast expressed through line density: dense parallel shadow fields, sparse highlight regions.\nCOLOR PALETTE: Black ink lines and white paper ground, with chrome implied via tonal linework only.\nCOMPOSITION: Maintain original composition exactly. Clean white background. Generous negative space.\nNEGATIVE: added elements, new accessories, color fills, soft painterly shading, stippling dots, noisy gradients, watercolor bleed, chains not present in source, spikes, weapons, wings, extra limbs, small text."],
  ["red_chrome", "[SUBJECT].\nRESTYLE ONLY — do not add, remove, or alter any elements of the original subject. Preserve exact composition, pose, and silhouette.\nSTYLE: Saturated single-hue red chrome rendering applied to existing subject only. 8k clarity.\nSURFACE & MATERIAL: Re-render all existing surfaces as polished candy-red chrome with wet lacquer sheen. Reflections move from deep crimson shadows to cherry-red mids and hot pink-white speculars. Keep smooth unbroken gradients without stipple or hatch.\nFORM TREATMENT: Existing edges and contours remain faithful while appearing dipped in liquid red chrome.\nLIGHTING: Soft studio lighting with smooth maroon-black shadow falloff and large white-pink hotspot highlights.\nCOLOR PALETTE: Candy red, deep crimson, cherry red, maroon-black, hot pink-white highlights only. Maximum 4-5 tonal values.\nCOMPOSITION: Maintain original composition exactly. Clean white background. Generous negative space.\nNEGATIVE: added elements, new accessories, chains, jewelry, ribbons, bows, glasses, spikes, weapons, wings, extra limbs, clothing not in original, fine-line clutter, stippling, crosshatching, intricate mechanics, small text, busy textures, dithering."],
  ["chain_chrome", "[SUBJECT].\nRESTYLE ONLY — do not add, remove, or alter any elements of the original subject. Preserve exact composition, pose, and silhouette.\nSTYLE: Chrome chain-texture integration rendering applied to existing subject only. 8k clarity.\nSURFACE & MATERIAL: Re-render existing surfaces as tightly interlocking polished chrome links that follow original contours like second-skin material replacement. Each link carries clean reflective hotspots and smooth metallic finish.\nFORM TREATMENT: Original silhouette and structure remain intact; chain-link pattern is a surface reinterpretation only. Do not introduce separate hanging chains or added adornments.\nLIGHTING: High-contrast studio light with deep occlusion between links and bright white specular hotspots on convex link surfaces.\nCOLOR PALETTE: Polished silver chrome, cool grey, deep black occlusion, bright white highlights only. Maximum 4-5 tonal values.\nCOMPOSITION: Maintain original composition exactly. Clean white background. Generous negative space.\nNEGATIVE: new accessories or dangling chain objects, jewelry additions, ribbons, bows, glasses, spikes, weapons, wings, extra limbs, clothing not in original, fine stipple, crosshatching, noisy gradients, dithering, dotwork, filigree."],
  ["cartoon_chrome", "[SUBJECT].\nRESTYLE ONLY — do not add, remove, or alter any elements of the original subject. Preserve exact composition, pose, and silhouette.\nSTYLE: Cartoonistic colored chrome rendering applied to existing subject only. 8k bold readability.\nSURFACE & MATERIAL: Re-render all existing surfaces as shiny chrome with saturated color-block zones (for example green chrome, pink chrome, gold chrome) and simplified graphic reflection bands. Keep smooth transitions without fine texture, stippling, or hatch.\nFORM TREATMENT: Existing contours remain faithful with slight inflated stylization while preserving silhouette. No added parts or appendages.\nLIGHTING: Bright even studio light. Clean graphic shadow gradients into darker saturated values. Large white hotspot highlights.\nCOLOR PALETTE: Saturated green chrome, hot pink chrome, gold chrome, deep black, white highlights. Maximum 4-5 colors.\nCOMPOSITION: Maintain original composition exactly. Clean white background. Generous negative space.\nNEGATIVE: added elements, new accessories, chains, jewelry, ribbons, bows, glasses, spikes, weapons, wings, extra limbs, clothing not in original, intricate mechanics, small text, noisy gradients, dithering, dotwork."],
  ["glassy_chrome", "[SUBJECT].\nRESTYLE ONLY — do not add, remove, or alter any elements of the original subject. Preserve exact composition, pose, and silhouette.\nSTYLE: See-through glassy chrome hybrid rendering applied to existing subject only. 8k clarity.\nSURFACE & MATERIAL: Re-render all existing surfaces as a controlled mix of clear glass and polished chrome. Some existing regions become transparent with visible internal form structure, while others remain opaque chrome reflective zones. Keep smooth transitions between clear and reflective regions.\nFORM TREATMENT: Existing contours and structure remain faithful. Transparency reveals existing internal form logic only; no invented internal organs or added components.\nLIGHTING: Soft studio light with subtle refractive caustic behavior in transparent areas and crisp chrome flashes in reflective areas.\nCOLOR PALETTE: Clear glass, polished silver chrome, cool blue refractive tint, deep black, bright white highlights only. Maximum 4-5 tonal values.\nCOMPOSITION: Maintain original composition exactly. Clean white background. Generous negative space.\nNEGATIVE: added elements, accessories, chains, jewelry, ribbons, bows, glasses, spikes, weapons, wings, extra limbs, clothing not in original, fine-line clutter, stippling, crosshatching, intricate mechanics, small text, noisy gradients, dotwork."],
  ["surreal_airbrush_chrome", "[SUBJECT].\nRESTYLE ONLY — do not add, remove, or alter any elements of the original subject. Preserve exact composition, pose, and silhouette.\nSTYLE: Surreal chrome airbrush rendering applied to existing subject only. Pulp art and fine-art photography influence. 8k clarity.\nSURFACE & MATERIAL: Re-render all existing surfaces as hyper-smooth glass-like airbrushed chrome with distorted dreamlike reflections across curvature. Preserve buttery gradients with zero grain, no stipple, and no hatch.\nFORM TREATMENT: Existing forms remain faithful while gaining surreal reflective character. No new parts, helmets, accessories, or appendages.\nLIGHTING: Cinematic low-key contrast with broad diffused highlights and deep controlled shadows.\nCOLOR PALETTE: Cool silver chrome, subtle warm flesh-tinted chrome notes, deep black, bright white reflections only. Maximum 4-5 tonal values.\nCOMPOSITION: Maintain original composition exactly. Fine-art framing feel with strong negative space.\nNEGATIVE: added elements, new accessories, chains, bows, ribbons, glasses, spikes, weapons, wings, extra limbs, clothing not in original, fine detail clutter, noisy gradients, dithering, dotwork, filigree."],
  ["rainbow_hue_chrome", "[SUBJECT].\nRESTYLE ONLY — do not add, remove, or alter any elements of the original subject. Preserve exact composition, pose, and silhouette.\nSTYLE: Chrome silver rendering with subtle rainbow-hue bleed through metallic base. 8k clarity.\nSURFACE & MATERIAL: Re-render all existing surfaces as mirror-polished silver chrome with delicate anodized spectral undertones (soft pink, gold, aqua, lavender). Keep rainbow cues subtle and organic, not loud. Smooth gradients only.\nFORM TREATMENT: Existing edges and contours remain faithful; no new forms or accessories.\nLIGHTING: Soft even studio light to reveal subtle hue shifts along curvature. Smooth deep-charcoal shadows and bright white peak highlights.\nCOLOR PALETTE: Silver chrome base, subtle rainbow undertones, deep charcoal, bright white highlights. Maximum 5-6 delicate tonal values.\nCOMPOSITION: Maintain original composition exactly. Clean white background. Generous negative space.\nNEGATIVE: added elements, new accessories, chains, jewelry, ribbons, bows, glasses, spikes, weapons, wings, extra limbs, clothing not in original, garish neon rainbow overload, stippling, crosshatching, intricate mechanics, small text, noisy gradients, dithering, dotwork."],
  ["condensation_chrome", "[SUBJECT].\nRESTYLE ONLY — do not add, remove, or alter any elements of the original subject. Preserve exact composition, pose, and silhouette.\nSTYLE: Colorful chrome microrealism with condensation effect on existing subject only. 8k clarity.\nSURFACE & MATERIAL: Re-render all existing surfaces as polished colorful chrome with realistic water droplet beading and streaking on top of the chrome finish. Droplets should feel cold, lens-like, and physically plausible. Keep underlying chrome gradients smooth.\nFORM TREATMENT: Existing forms remain faithful and recognizable. No added objects or accessories.\nLIGHTING: Soft studio light with dual specular systems: chrome body highlights and micro-highlights on each droplet.\nCOLOR PALETTE: Vivid chrome hues aligned to subject, silver base reflections, deep shadows, bright white droplet highlights. Maximum 5-6 tonal values.\nCOMPOSITION: Maintain original composition exactly. Clean white background. Generous negative space.\nNEGATIVE: added elements, new accessories, chains, jewelry, ribbons, bows, glasses, spikes, weapons, wings, extra limbs, clothing not in original, stippling, crosshatching, intricate mechanics, small text, busy patterns, dithering, dotwork."],
  ["melting_face_chrome", "[SUBJECT].\nRESTYLE ONLY — do not add, remove, or alter any elements of the original subject. Preserve exact composition, pose, and silhouette.\nSTYLE: Hyper-realistic melting chrome fusion rendering applied to existing subject only. 8k bold clarity.\nSURFACE & MATERIAL: Re-render all surfaces as ultra-polished viscous chrome in active melt state. Reflections are high-contrast black/grey with bright white pinpoints. Drips remain mercury-like and cohesive.\nFORM TREATMENT: Core subject stays recognizable and faithful while periphery and low points dissolve into controlled liquid chrome flow. No new parts or external objects.\nLIGHTING: Cinematic sharp-edged lighting with reflective hotspot detail on chrome bulges and drips.\nCOLOR PALETTE: Gunmetal chrome, rose-warm chrome tints, deep black, bright white highlights only. Maximum 4-5 tonal values.\nCOMPOSITION: Maintain original composition exactly. Clean white background. Generous negative space.\nNEGATIVE: added elements, new accessories, chains, jewelry, ribbons, bows, glasses, spikes, weapons, wings, extra limbs, clothing not in original, fine-line clutter, stippling, crosshatching, intricate mechanics, small text, noisy gradients, dithering, dotwork."],
  ["dual_tone_chrome", "[SUBJECT].\nRESTYLE ONLY — do not add, remove, or alter any elements of the original subject. Preserve exact composition, pose, and silhouette.\nSTYLE: Ornate dual-tone chrome rendering using gold and silver interplay over existing forms only. 8k clarity.\nSURFACE & MATERIAL: Re-render all existing surfaces as polished mirror-reflective bi-metal chrome, with warm gold and cool silver zones divided along natural contour boundaries. Keep broad smooth gradients and clear material separation.\nFORM TREATMENT: Existing structure remains faithful. No added ornaments, parts, or accessories.\nLIGHTING: Dramatic contrast against black field. Warm-tinted mirror flashes on gold regions and cool-tinted flashes on silver regions.\nCOLOR PALETTE: Rich gold chrome, cool silver chrome, deep jet black, warm white and cool white highlights only. Maximum 5 tonal values.\nCOMPOSITION: Maintain original composition exactly. Clean black background. Dramatic negative space.\nNEGATIVE: added elements, new accessories, chains, jewelry, ribbons, bows, glasses, spikes, weapons, wings, extra limbs, clothing not in original, fine-line clutter, stippling, crosshatching, intricate mechanics, small text, busy textures, dithering, dotwork."],
  ["lego_chrome", "[SUBJECT].\nRESTYLE ONLY — do not add, remove, or alter subject matter. Preserve original composition and overall silhouette.\nSTYLE: Chrome block-construction rendering applied to existing subject only. 8k clarity.\nSURFACE & MATERIAL: Re-render surfaces as shiny chrome-plated block modules with independent reflections per block face. Keep polished metallic finish and clear geometric separation between modules.\nFORM TREATMENT: Preserve overall proportions and recognizability while voxelizing surface resolution into block-based geometry. No added accessories, appendages, or unrelated objects.\nLIGHTING: High-contrast studio lighting. Shadow pockets between blocks for depth. Bright white specular flashes on top and side block planes.\nCOLOR PALETTE: Polished silver chrome, cool grey, deep black between blocks, bright white highlights only. Maximum 4-5 tonal values.\nCOMPOSITION: Maintain original composition exactly. Clean white background. Generous negative space.\nNEGATIVE: added elements, new accessories, chains, jewelry, ribbons, bows, glasses, spikes, weapons, wings, extra limbs, clothing not in original, colorization, stippling, crosshatching, intricate mechanics, small text, noisy gradients, dithering, dotwork."],
  ["sumie_ink_dragon", "[SUBJECT]. RESTYLE ONLY — do not add, remove, or alter any elements of the original subject. No new objects, accessories, or compositional elements. Preserve the exact subject identity, pose, and silhouette. STYLE: Japanese sumi-e ink calligraphy rendering applied to the existing subject. Brush-loaded ink treatment with the energy of gestural calligraphy but the clarity of clean tattoo design. 8k resolution. MEDIUM: Pure black ink on bright white. No color. Only black, white, and smooth grey wash gradients. INK TECHNIQUE: Re-render the existing subject using two systems: (1) Confident single-stroke calligraphic sweeps for existing contours — THICK strokes varying from medium to broad. No hairline strokes. (2) Solid black fill areas for dense zones within the original subject — large masses of unbroken black. GREY VALUES: Where midtones are needed on existing forms, use smooth ink-wash gradients — wet, diffused, bleeding gently into white. Maximum 3 tonal steps: black, grey wash, white paper. MOVEMENT: Capture any existing energy in the original subject's pose. Flowing brushwork follows the original forms. Trailing ink marks may extend slightly into negative space but remain MEDIUM-weight. SILHOUETTE TEST: The original subject's silhouette must remain recognizable and powerful when squinted at. DRY BRUSH: Where bristle-texture marks appear on existing forms, they are bold and chunky. COMPOSITION: Maintain original composition. Massive white negative space. No background. NEGATIVE: added elements, new accessories, clouds, waves, flowers, ornaments not in original, extra creatures, fine crosshatching, stippling, thin lines, hairline details, complex internal rendering, small-scale texture, color, busy composition, noisy gradients."],
  ["crystal_glass", "[SUBJECT].\nRESTYLE ONLY — do not add, remove, or alter any elements of the original subject. Preserve exact composition, pose, and silhouette.\nSTYLE: Hyper-realistic sculptural object carved entirely from solid, optical-grade crystal glass. Ultra-realistic 3D render. 8k resolution.\nSURFACE & MATERIAL: Re-render the existing subject as solid, heavy, dense optical-grade crystal glass. The object preserves its true proportions and recognizable silhouette with precise geometry and clean edge definition appropriate to its form. The glass feels heavy, dense, and premium — never plastic, never stylized, never neon.\nLIGHTING & VALUE: Low-key studio lighting with a single focused directional white light source entering the object from one direction, refracting through the internal volume. Produces layered internal reflections, chromatic aberration, and physically accurate spectral dispersion along edges, corners, and internal transitions. Light bends, splits, and bounces naturally within the material. A small, intense specular highlight appears on a sharp edge or curvature where light strikes most directly, producing a crisp optical spark. Lighting is minimal and studio-controlled, designed to emphasize form, refraction, internal depth, and edge clarity rather than brightness.\nINTERNAL DETAIL: Inside the glass, subtle volumetric depth is visible — faint internal reflections, refractive distortions, micro-scratches, and tiny dust particles suspended within the material. Rainbow dispersion comes only from white light refraction, never artificially colored.\nFORM TREATMENT: Object floating at a slight dynamic angle, not perfectly straight, allowing light interaction across multiple surfaces. Reflections are sharp and physically accurate.\nBACKGROUND: Pure black void with soft falloff and no visible environment.\nCOMPOSITION: Maintain original composition. Subject isolated against pure black. Dramatic negative space.\nNEGATIVE: added elements, new accessories, text, logos, markings, neon colors, artificial coloring, plastic appearance, stylized rendering, flat lighting, matte surface, cartoon, illustration, painterly, bright background, visible environment."],
  ["traditional", "[SUBJECT].\nSTYLE: Classic American Traditional tattoo. Bold, clean, iconic. Sailor Jerry heritage. Flat on white background as a tattoo flash sheet design.\nLINEWORK: Thick, unwavering black outlines. Uniform line weight throughout. Every line is confident, deliberate, and perfectly smooth. No sketchy or broken lines. Lines are the backbone — they dominate the composition.\nCOLOR PALETTE: Strictly limited to: rich saturated red, deep hunter green, warm golden yellow, dense solid black, and untouched white skin-tone negative space. No gradients between colors. No pastels. No purple. No pink. No blue unless navy.\nSHADING: Black shading only. Smooth whip-shading gradients from solid black to skin using parallel curved lines (not crosshatch). Classic \"moon shading\" crescents on rounded forms. No grey wash — only black fading to open skin.\nFILL: Large areas of flat, solid, unbroken color. No texture inside color fields. Color sits heavy and saturated like thick ink packed into skin.\nCOMPOSITION: Subject completely isolated on a clean white background. Designed as a standalone tattoo flash piece. Symmetrical where possible. Compact, readable silhouette.\nRENDERING: Two-dimensional with implied depth through shading crescents only. No realistic lighting, no ambient occlusion, no reflected light. Forms are simplified and iconic, not anatomically precise.\nNEGATIVE: photorealistic, 3D rendering, soft shading, airbrush gradients, thin lines, sketch lines, watercolor, splatter, geometric patterns, dotwork, fine detail texture, purple, pink, pastel colors, grey wash, realistic fur or hair texture."],
  ["neo_traditional", "[SUBJECT].\nSTYLE: Neo-Traditional tattoo. Evolved traditional with expanded artistry. Art Nouveau and Art Deco influenced. Bold yet ornate. Flat on white background.\nLINEWORK: Thick black outlines as the structural foundation, but with deliberate variation in line weight — thicker on outer contours, slightly thinner for internal detail. Smooth, confident, flowing lines. Decorative line flourishes and filigree where appropriate.\nCOLOR PALETTE: Expanded rich palette beyond traditional: deep jewel tones — burgundy, teal, burnt orange, plum purple, dusty rose, sage green, mustard gold, navy blue. Colors are saturated but slightly more nuanced than old-school. Smooth gradients allowed between analogous colors.\nSHADING: Smooth gradient shading from black through grey tones to open skin. More sophisticated tonal range than traditional. Soft blended transitions within outlined sections. Dimensional but still graphic, not photorealistic.\nDETAIL: Significantly more internal detail than traditional. Decorative elements: ornamental filigree, Art Nouveau flowing organic curves, jewels, gems, botanical flourishes, mandala-adjacent patterns. Fine detail within bold structural outlines.\nRENDERING: Illustrative with enhanced dimensionality. Richer tonal modeling than flat traditional, but still fundamentally a bold outlined tattoo — not realism. Faces and features are stylized but expressive.\nCOMPOSITION: Subject isolated on clean white background. Decorative framing elements welcome. Flowing, organic overall shape.\nNEGATIVE: photorealistic, thin fine-line only, no outlines, watercolor splatter, trash polka, geometric minimalism, sketchy lines, digital painting, airbrush smooth, cartoon, anime."],
  ["japanese", "[SUBJECT].\nSTYLE: Traditional Japanese Irezumi tattoo. Ukiyo-e woodblock print influence. Centuries-old iconographic tradition. Flat on white background.\nLINEWORK: Clean, flowing black outlines with deliberate variation — thicker on external contours (fukibokashi), thinner on internal details. Lines follow the natural flow and movement of the subject. Every line implies motion and energy like wind or water current.\nCOLOR PALETTE: Traditional Japanese palette: deep indigo blue, vermillion red, muted sage green, warm ochre gold, soft peach skin tones, charcoal black. Colors are rich but slightly muted and earthy, never neon or overly bright. Large areas of black (tsubushi) for contrast.\nSHADING: Smooth gradual gradients (bokashi) fading from solid color to open skin. No hard edges on shading — everything transitions like watercolor on silk. Background elements use extensive grey-wash gradients. Wind bars and cloud formations use classic graduated shading.\nBACKGROUND: Integrate traditional Japanese background elements: flowing water, wind bars (kaze), rolling clouds (kumo), cherry blossoms (sakura petals scattered), maple leaves (momiji), waves (nami), or chrysanthemum patterns. Background fills negative space with atmospheric depth.\nCOMPOSITION: Subject isolated on white background but composed as if it belongs in a full Japanese bodysuit sleeve — dynamic diagonal energy, flowing directional movement, asymmetric balance. Subject should feel like it's in motion.\nRENDERING: Flat illustrative with atmospheric depth through gradients. Woodblock print aesthetic. Not photorealistic. Stylized anatomy following Irezumi conventions.\nNEGATIVE: photorealistic, American traditional flat color, geometric, minimalist, thin fine-line, dotwork, tribal, sketch style, digital art, 3D rendering, neon colors."],
  ["tattoo_blackwork", "[SUBJECT].\nSTYLE: Bold Blackwork tattoo. Pure black ink only. Maximum visual impact through stark contrast. Flat on white background.\nLINEWORK: Confident, clean black lines ranging from medium to very bold weight. Lines define structure and silhouette. No grey, no color — only pitch black ink and white negative space.\nFILL: Large areas of dense, solid, unbroken black. Black should appear absolute — no streaks, no patchiness. The interplay between filled black shapes and preserved white skin negative space IS the design.\nSHADING: No grey wash. Shading is achieved ONLY through: solid black vs white, stipple dot density variation, parallel line hatching, or crosshatching. Tonal gradients created through mark density, not ink dilution.\nTEXTURE: Heavy, graphic, powerful. Think bold poster design or linocut print. High contrast silhouettes. Black areas feel heavy and dense. White areas feel deliberately preserved and purposeful.\nCOMPOSITION: Subject completely isolated on clean white background. Strong, readable silhouette at any size. Negative space is as important as positive space — both are deliberately designed.\nRENDERING: Flat graphic with no attempt at photorealism. Bold, iconic, and powerful. Simplified forms reduced to their essential shapes. Every element is either solid black or white — no middle ground.\nNEGATIVE: color, grey wash, soft shading, gradients, fine-line delicate, watercolor, photorealistic, 3D, airbrush, pastel, light grey, sketchy, thin wispy lines."],
  ["tattoo_dotwork", "[SUBJECT].\nSTYLE: Precision Dotwork tattoo. Entire image constructed from individual dots. Meditative, mathematical beauty. Flat on white background.\nLINEWORK: Minimal to no continuous lines. All form, shading, and detail achieved through carefully placed individual dots. Structural outlines, if present, are formed by tightly packed dot sequences rather than solid lines.\nTECHNIQUE: Stippling at its highest level. Every tonal value is created by dot density — closely packed dots for deep shadows, gradually spacing dots further apart for lighter tones, and open white space for highlights. Each dot should feel deliberately placed.\nSHADING: Smooth gradients achieved exclusively through dot density variation. Dark areas: dots nearly touching, creating near-solid fields. Mid-tones: evenly spaced dots. Light areas: sparse, widely spaced dots fading into clean white. Transitions must be smooth and seamless despite being made of discrete points.\nTEXTURE: The dot texture itself is the aesthetic. Dots should be uniform in size (unless deliberately varied for effect). The cumulative effect creates an almost photographic tonal range while remaining visibly dotted at close inspection.\nCOMPOSITION: Subject completely isolated on clean white background. Often incorporates geometric frameworks, sacred geometry underlying structures, or mandala-influenced compositions.\nRENDERING: Meditative precision. Not photorealistic and not cartoon — a unique aesthetic that is simultaneously mechanical and organic. The patience and precision of the technique should be visible.\nNEGATIVE: solid lines, solid black fill, color, watercolor, sketch lines, crosshatch, smooth airbrush shading, bold outlines, traditional tattoo style, splatter, smudge."],
  ["tattoo_geometric", "[SUBJECT].\nSTYLE: Geometric tattoo. Subject deconstructed into precise geometric shapes. Mathematical beauty meets organic form. Flat on white background.\nLINEWORK: Ultra-precise, razor-sharp straight lines and perfect geometric curves. Uniform thin-to-medium line weight. Every line is mathematically exact — no wobble, no hand-drawn imperfection. Lines intersect at precise angles.\nCONSTRUCTION: Subject is built from or deconstructed into geometric primitives: triangles, circles, hexagons, diamonds, parallel lines, and polygonal facets. The subject should be recognizable but abstracted through geometric language. Think low-poly 3D rendering meets architectural drafting.\nSHADING: Flat fills within geometric sections. Adjacent facets use different tonal values (solid black, grey tones, white) to create dimensional illusion through contrast, like a faceted gemstone. No smooth gradients — each geometric section has a single uniform tone.\nSYMMETRY: Strong emphasis on mathematical symmetry, balance, and pattern. Golden ratio proportions. Bilateral or radial symmetry where the subject allows.\nCOMPOSITION: Subject completely isolated on clean white background. Geometric precision with clean, intentional negative space. The design should feel engineered and deliberate.\nRENDERING: Architectural and precise. Not organic or hand-drawn looking. Every element feels calculated and intentional. The beauty is in the mathematical perfection.\nNEGATIVE: organic flowing lines, watercolor, sketch, soft shading, gradients, photorealistic, traditional bold outlines, splatter, rough texture, hand-drawn aesthetic, smudge."],
  ["tattoo_watercolor", "[SUBJECT].\nSTYLE: Watercolor tattoo. Fluid, painterly, organic. Fine art watercolor painting translated to skin. Flat on white background.\nLINEWORK: Minimal black structural lines — thin, delicate, and intentionally incomplete. Lines may break and trail off. Some areas defined purely by color edges with no outline at all. Where present, lines are fine and elegant, not bold.\nCOLOR: Vivid, translucent watercolor washes. Colors bleed and bloom into each other organically. Visible color gradients flowing wet-into-wet. Palette is bright and expressive — turquoise, magenta, golden yellow, coral, violet, emerald. Colors appear to float and diffuse on the white background.\nTECHNIQUE: Visible paint behaviors: color bleeds, wet edges, pigment pooling at boundaries, splatter droplets, drip runs, dry brush strokes, granulation texture. Edges of the design dissolve into splashes and spatters that trail off into white space.\nSHADING: Achieved through layered transparent washes, not black shading. Depth comes from overlapping translucent color layers where colors mix optically. Some areas intentionally left as white paper showing through.\nEDGES: Soft, undefined boundaries. The design has no hard border — it bleeds, splashes, and dissolves into the white background organically. Paint splatters and droplets extend beyond the main subject.\nCOMPOSITION: Subject isolated on white background. The watercolor effects (splashes, drips, bleeds) create an organic, asymmetric frame around the subject. White space is deliberately preserved.\nNEGATIVE: bold black outlines, solid flat color fills, traditional tattoo style, geometric precision, heavy black shading, photorealistic, clean hard edges, blackwork, dotwork, uniform line weight."],
  ["realism", "[SUBJECT].\nSTYLE: Photorealistic tattoo. Indistinguishable from a high-resolution photograph. Master-level realism. Flat on white background.\nLINEWORK: No visible outlines or drawn lines whatsoever. Form is defined purely through tonal value, light, and shadow — exactly as in a photograph. Zero cartoon or illustrative line quality.\nSHADING: Full continuous tonal range from absolute black to pure white. Smooth, seamless gradients. Every surface has accurate light behavior — soft shadows, core shadows, reflected light, ambient occlusion, specular highlights. The rendering should look like a black-and-white photograph.\nDETAIL: Microscopic precision. Render every surface texture with photographic accuracy: individual hair strands, skin pores, fabric weave, metal reflections, wood grain, wet surfaces, translucent materials. Detail density should match an 8K macro photograph.\nLIGHTING: Cinematic studio lighting. Clear, directional key light creating defined highlight and shadow. Subtle fill light preventing pure black crush in shadows. Rim light or backlight separating subject from background where appropriate.\nDEPTH: Realistic depth of field. Primary focal point razor-sharp, subtle softening in background or peripheral areas. Atmospheric perspective for depth.\nCOMPOSITION: Subject completely isolated on clean white background. The realism of the subject contrasted against pure white creates a powerful floating effect.\nRENDERING: This must be indistinguishable from a photograph at first glance. Every material, every texture, every lighting interaction must be physically accurate.\nNEGATIVE: outlines, cartoon, illustrative, flat color, traditional tattoo, stylized, abstract, geometric, watercolor, bold lines, simplified forms, low detail."],
  ["tattoo_trash_polka", "[SUBJECT].\nSTYLE: Trash Polka tattoo. Originated by Buena Vista Tattoo Club (Simone Pfaff & Volko Merschky). Chaotic collage of realism and graphic abstraction. Flat on white background.\nCOLOR PALETTE: Strictly black, grey, and red ONLY. No other colors. Dense black ink, smooth grey washes, and aggressive strokes of bold saturated red. The red acts as violent accent slashes against monochromatic realism.\nCOMPOSITION: Collage-style layering. Realistic rendered subject combined with: bold graphic red brush strokes, paint smears, typographic fragments, geometric shapes, splatter, drip marks, halftone dot patterns, newspaper texture, smudged ink. Organized chaos — every element is deliberately placed to create controlled disorder.\nREALISM LAYER: The core subject rendered in detailed black-and-grey realism — photographic quality faces, eyes, textures, anatomical accuracy.\nABSTRACT LAYER: Overlaid with aggressive abstract elements — thick red paint strokes slashing across the composition, black ink splatters, geometric red and black shapes, torn paper edges, stamp-like graphic blocks, distressed texture overlays.\nTEXTURE: Mixed media collage feel. Combine smooth realistic rendering with rough graphic textures — halftone dots, newspaper print, rubber stamp marks, stencil edges, paint roller texture, xerox distortion.\nNEGATIVE: full color, traditional outlines, clean and minimal, watercolor softness, geometric precision, Japanese style, neo-traditional, cute, delicate, symmetrical, pastel."],
  ["tribal", "[SUBJECT].\nSTYLE: Tribal tattoo. Bold, primal, iconic. Inspired by Polynesian, Maori, Borneo, and Pacific Islander traditions. Flat on white background.\nLINEWORK: No traditional outlines. The design IS the solid black shapes. Forms are defined by the edges of bold, sweeping black shapes against white negative space.\nFILL: Massive areas of dense, solid, absolute black ink. Tribal is defined by its heavy black saturation. Shapes are organic, flowing, pointed — tapering from thick to thin like flames or ocean waves.\nPATTERN: Subject translated into flowing, interlocking black shapes with pointed tips, curved hooks, spear points, and wave-like flowing forms. Incorporate traditional motifs: spearheads, ocean waves, shark teeth (niho mano), sun rays, tiki forms, koru spirals.\nNEGATIVE SPACE: The white space between black shapes is as important as the black itself. Clean, deliberate channels of white cut through the black, creating rhythm and visual flow. White channels are smooth and uniform.\nFLOW: Every shape flows into the next with organic, muscular energy. Shapes follow body contour conventions — tapering, curving, radiating. The overall composition should feel like it's in motion, like flame or water.\nCOMPOSITION: Subject isolated on clean white background. Design should feel like it wraps and flows, suggesting three-dimensional body placement even on a flat surface.\nNEGATIVE: color, grey shading, fine lines, delicate detail, photorealistic, watercolor, geometric precision, dotwork, illustrative, sketch, thin lines, gradients."],
  ["chicano", "[SUBJECT].\nSTYLE: Chicano tattoo. Born from Mexican-American street culture and fine art traditions. Smooth black-and-grey elegance. Flat on white background.\nLINEWORK: Clean, precise single-needle fine lines. Thin, sharp, and elegant. Delicate line weight for details — eyelashes, lip lines, hair strands, script flourishes. Outlines are present but refined, never bold or heavy.\nSHADING: Masterful smooth black-and-grey wash. Silky gradient transitions from deep black through every grey tone to white. No harsh transitions — everything blends like airbrushed silk. The shading quality is the hallmark of Chicano style. Smooth as polished stone.\nPALETTE: Strictly black and grey. No color. Full greyscale range utilized with supreme smoothness. Deep blacks in shadows, luminous greys in mid-tones, bright white highlights.\nAESTHETIC: Cultural iconography: lowrider culture, religious imagery (praying hands, Virgin Mary, rosaries, crosses), script lettering with decorative flourishes, roses, sugar skulls, clown faces (payaso/payasa), city skylines, dice, playing cards, money roses, clock faces.\nDETAIL: Fine single-needle detail work. Intricate eyelashes, realistic eyes with catch-lights, detailed lip texture, individual hair strands, lace patterns, filigree script, rosary bead reflections.\nCOMPOSITION: Subject isolated on white background. Elegant and composed. Often framed with script banners, rose elements, or religious iconographic framing.\nNEGATIVE: bold thick outlines, flat color, bright colors, traditional style, geometric, abstract, heavy blackwork, tribal, watercolor, cartoon, rough texture."],
  ["new_school", "[SUBJECT].\nSTYLE: New School tattoo. Exaggerated, cartoonish, vibrant. Graffiti-meets-tattoo energy. Wild proportions and electric color. Flat on white background.\nLINEWORK: Bold, confident black outlines — thick and animated. Lines have dynamic variation: extra thick on outer contours, thinner for internal detail. Lines are smooth and flowing with exaggerated curves. Everything feels inflated and bouncy.\nCOLOR PALETTE: Extremely vivid, saturated, borderline neon. Electric blues, hot pinks, acid greens, bright oranges, vivid purples, sunshine yellows. Colors pop aggressively. Heavy use of color gradients and blends within outlined sections.\nPROPORTIONS: Deliberately exaggerated and distorted. Large heads, big eyes, oversized features, inflated round forms, tiny bodies if humorous. Think cartoon caricature meets graffiti character design. Nothing is anatomically correct — everything is stylized for maximum expression and energy.\nSHADING: Smooth color gradients within outlined sections. White highlight spots (shine dots) on rounded surfaces. Color-to-color blending. Some areas use complementary color shading rather than black shading. Overall effect is glossy, plastic, inflated.\nENERGY: Maximum visual energy. Dynamic poses, exaggerated expressions, motion lines, speed streaks. Everything feels alive, animated, and bursting with personality.\nCOMPOSITION: Subject isolated on white background. Dynamic, asymmetric pose. The subject should feel like it's about to leap off the page.\nNEGATIVE: realistic proportions, muted colors, fine-line delicate, photorealistic, Japanese traditional, geometric, minimalist, black-and-grey, serious, subtle, monochromatic."],
  ["tattoo_biomech", "[SUBJECT].\nSTYLE: Biomechanical tattoo. H.R. Giger inspired. Fusion of organic flesh and mechanical engineering. Flat on white background.\nLINEWORK: Detailed, precise lines defining both organic tissue and mechanical components. Line weight varies — heavier for structural mechanical elements, finer for tissue and tendons. Lines follow the implied three-dimensional form of exposed anatomy and machinery.\nRENDERING: Highly detailed, semi-realistic rendering. Mechanical components (gears, pistons, cables, circuit boards, hydraulic cylinders, ball joints) interwoven with organic elements (muscle fibers, tendons, bones, veins, tissue layers). The two fuse seamlessly — flesh becomes machine, machine becomes flesh.\nSHADING: Full tonal range, realistic lighting on both organic and mechanical surfaces. Metallic highlights and reflections on chrome and steel. Wet, glistening quality on exposed organic tissue. Deep shadows in recessed mechanical cavities. Strong directional lighting.\nTEXTURE: Extreme texture differentiation. Smooth polished metal vs. fibrous muscle tissue vs. ribbed cables vs. porous bone vs. translucent membrane. Each material is rendered with its unique surface quality.\nDEPTH: The design should appear to reveal layers beneath the surface — as if skin has been peeled back or torn away to expose the biomechanical interior. Create convincing three-dimensional depth through overlapping layers, shadows, and perspective.\nCOMPOSITION: Subject isolated on white background. The biomechanical elements should integrate with the subject's natural form, following anatomical logic.\nNEGATIVE: flat color, cartoon, traditional tattoo, tribal, minimalist, watercolor, geometric patterns, simple, clean, cute, bright colors, 2D flat rendering."],
  ["illustrative", "[SUBJECT].\nSTYLE: Illustrative tattoo. Fine art illustration translated to skin. Storybook, editorial, or graphic novel quality. Flat on white background.\nLINEWORK: Expressive, varied line weight. A mix of confident bold strokes and delicate fine details. Lines have artistic character — they feel hand-drawn by a skilled illustrator, not mechanical. Visible ink quality with intentional line variation.\nSHADING: Mixed technique shading: crosshatching, parallel hatching, stipple dots, and selective smooth washes. The shading technique itself is part of the aesthetic — visible mark-making rather than hidden blending. Think pen-and-ink illustration with selective wash.\nDETAIL: Rich illustrative detail. Fine crosshatch textures, detailed linework patterns, decorative elements. The level of detail should match a high-quality book illustration or editorial artwork. Every area has visual interest.\nAESTHETIC: Fine art print quality. Could exist as a standalone illustration in a gallery, book, or editorial publication. References illustration traditions: botanical illustration, scientific illustration, storybook art, editorial cartoon, graphic novel, Art Nouveau poster.\nCOLOR: If color is used, it's applied like watercolor or gouache illustration — selective, artistic, not filling every space. Color works with the linework, not replacing it. Alternatively, pure black ink illustration is equally valid.\nCOMPOSITION: Subject isolated on white background. Composed like a fine art print. May include decorative framing elements, botanical borders, or banner elements typical of illustration tradition.\nNEGATIVE: photorealistic smooth blending, bold traditional outlines with flat fill, geometric, tribal, minimalist empty, airbrush smooth, digital art aesthetic, neon colors, cartoon exaggeration."],
  ["fine_line", "[SUBJECT].\nSTYLE: Fine Line minimalist tattoo. Delicate, precise, understated elegance. Single-needle aesthetic. Flat on white background.\nLINEWORK: Ultra-thin, precise, single-needle lines. Consistent hair-thin line weight throughout. Lines are clean, sharp, and unbroken. No bold outlines anywhere. The entire design is constructed from whisper-thin black lines of uniform weight.\nSHADING: Minimal to none. Where shading exists, it's achieved through: very fine stipple dots, extremely light parallel hatching, or sparse single-needle whip shading. Large areas of clean white negative space. The design breathes.\nDETAIL: Selective precision. Not every area is detailed — the beauty is in what's included AND what's left out. Essential forms captured with minimal marks. Each line must be necessary and intentional. Nothing superfluous.\nAESTHETIC: Clean, contemporary, refined. The visual equivalent of a whisper. Feels like a precise technical pen drawing. Instagram-era elegance. Modern, minimal, sophisticated.\nNEGATIVE SPACE: Dominant. The white background and open space ARE the design as much as the lines. Generous breathing room around and within the subject. Nothing feels crowded or heavy.\nCOMPOSITION: Subject isolated on white background with abundant negative space. Small-to-medium scale. Centered and balanced. The composition should feel light and airy.\nNEGATIVE: bold outlines, heavy black, solid fill, color, watercolor splatter, tribal, traditional bold, heavy shading, blackwork, crosshatch, dense detail, busy, cluttered."],
  ["tattoo_surrealism", "[SUBJECT].\nSTYLE: Surrealist tattoo. Salvador Dalí meets skin art. Dreamlike, impossible, visually paradoxical. Flat on white background.\nRENDERING: Photorealistic rendering technique applied to impossible or dreamlike subject matter. The technical execution is precise and realistic, but the content defies reality. This contrast between realistic technique and surreal content is the core aesthetic.\nSHADING: Full realistic tonal range. Smooth, sophisticated shading with complete value spectrum. Lighting behaves realistically even on impossible subjects — shadows, reflections, and highlights follow physical light rules applied to non-physical scenarios.\nCONCEPT: The subject should feel like a lucid dream or optical illusion. Elements may: melt, morph, fragment, float, dissolve, transform into other objects, exist at impossible scales, merge with unrelated objects, or defy physics. Reality is bent but rendered convincingly.\nTEXTURE: Realistic material rendering. Whatever surfaces exist (skin, stone, water, glass, metal, organic tissue) are rendered with photographic accuracy — making the surreal elements feel disturbingly real and tangible.\nDEPTH: Strong sense of three-dimensional space, potentially with impossible perspectives (Escher-like spatial paradoxes). Atmospheric depth through haze or scale change. The scene should feel like a real space containing impossible things.\nCOMPOSITION: Subject isolated on white background. The surreal elements should flow organically from the subject rather than feeling randomly assembled.\nNEGATIVE: cartoon, flat color, bold outlines, traditional tattoo, tribal, geometric pattern, minimalist, abstract non-representational, watercolor loose, low detail."],
  ["woodcut", "[SUBJECT].\nSTYLE: Woodcut / Linocut print tattoo. Medieval and Renaissance printmaking aesthetic. Bold carved graphic power. Flat on white background.\nLINEWORK: Lines that feel carved, not drawn. Bold, slightly rough-edged strokes that mimic wood or linoleum block carving. Lines have the characteristic slight irregularity of a relief print — not perfectly smooth, but confidently executed.\nTECHNIQUE: The entire image uses the visual language of relief printing: solid black areas are the uncarved surface (ink), white areas are carved-away channels (no ink). All tonal variation achieved through carved line patterns — parallel lines, crosshatching, and carved texture patterns.\nSHADING: No smooth gradients. All shading through carved line density: closely spaced parallel lines for darker areas, widely spaced lines for lighter areas. Crosshatching for deep shadows. White carved channels for highlights. Think Albrecht Dürer engravings.\nTEXTURE: Visible carved quality. Lines feel physical — like ink pressed from a carved block. Slight ink spread at line edges. The mechanical quality of printmaking is part of the beauty. Dense, rich, tactile.\nAESTHETIC: Historical print references: medieval woodcuts, Dürer engravings, Japanese woodblock (mokuhanga), Arts and Crafts movement prints, Mexican printmaking (José Guadalupe Posada). Bold, graphic, timeless.\nCOMPOSITION: Subject isolated on white background. Strong graphic silhouette. The image should feel like it could be stamped or printed from a hand-carved block.\nNEGATIVE: smooth gradients, airbrush, photorealistic, soft shading, watercolor, delicate fine lines, color gradients, modern digital aesthetic, clean vector lines, thin uniform lines."],
  ["ignorant", "[SUBJECT].\nSTYLE: Ignorant Style tattoo. Deliberately crude, punk aesthetic, anti-art charm. Stick-and-poke DIY energy. Flat on white background.\nLINEWORK: Intentionally rough, wobbly, uneven lines. Lines look hand-poked or drawn by an untrained hand — but with deliberate artistic intent. Varying line weight from thick to thin without consistency. Lines may not fully connect. Shaky, charming, raw.\nSHADING: Minimal. When present, rough stipple dots or messy scribble fill. No smooth gradients. Shading looks like it was done with a ballpoint pen in a notebook. Imperfect, patchy, uneven fill.\nAESTHETIC: Punk zine, bathroom graffiti, prison tattoo, notebook doodle, underground comic. The crude execution IS the style — it's intentionally anti-polished. Charming in its rawness. Funny, irreverent, counterculture.\nDETAIL: Low detail, simplified forms. Subject reduced to its most basic recognizable elements. Think how a teenager would draw it in a school notebook — simplified but identifiable. Bold, simple, immediate.\nFILL: If areas are filled, the fill is visibly imperfect — scratchy, uneven, with gaps showing white underneath. Hand-poked stipple dots rather than machine-smooth fill.\nCOMPOSITION: Subject isolated on white background. Small to medium scale. Casual, off-center placement is fine — precision is antithetical to the style.\nNEGATIVE: photorealistic, smooth shading, precise lines, professional polish, clean execution, fine detail, sophisticated technique, watercolor, geometric precision, Japanese traditional, neo-traditional ornate."],
  ["tattoo_ornamental", "[SUBJECT].\nSTYLE: Ornamental tattoo. Decorative, intricate, jewel-like precision. Henna, mandala, and architectural ornament traditions. Flat on white background.\nLINEWORK: Extremely precise, uniform fine-to-medium black lines. Mathematical accuracy in every curve and point. Lines form intricate repeating patterns with perfect consistency. Every line is deliberate and precisely placed.\nPATTERN: Dense ornamental patterning: mandala radiating designs, paisley motifs, mehndi/henna-inspired flowing patterns, lace textures, filigree scrollwork, arabesque geometric florals, dotwork accents within pattern fields.\nSYMMETRY: Strong bilateral or radial symmetry. Patterns mirror and repeat with mathematical precision. The overall design feels balanced, harmonious, and meditative in its repetition.\nDETAIL: Extremely high density of fine detail. Layer upon layer of intricate pattern work. Fine dots, tiny circles, delicate leaf forms, precise geometric fills. The closer you look, the more detail emerges.\nFILL: Patterns fill and define the subject's form. The subject shape is the container for ornamental pattern rather than being outlined and shaded traditionally. Different ornamental pattern types fill different areas to create tonal variation and visual interest.\nCOMPOSITION: Subject isolated on white background. The ornamental detail creates the form. Perfect symmetry and balance. Clean, precise edges where pattern meets white space.\nNEGATIVE: rough lines, bold traditional outlines, photorealistic, watercolor, splatter, messy, tribal bold shapes, cartoon, sketch, thick uneven lines, color fills, graffiti."],
  ["tattoo_sketch", "[SUBJECT].\nSTYLE: Sketch Style tattoo. Looks like a raw artist's sketchbook drawing. Unfinished, energetic, spontaneous. Flat on white background.\nLINEWORK: Multiple overlapping sketch lines rather than single clean outlines. Construction lines, gesture lines, and corrective redrawn lines are all visible — as if the artist drew the subject freehand without erasing. Some lines are darker and more committed, others are lighter exploratory marks.\nSHADING: Loose, rapid hatching and crosshatching. Scribble-style shading that follows the form but feels spontaneous rather than careful. Some areas left completely unshaded (unfinished). Shading density varies — some sections are worked up, others barely suggested.\nAESTHETIC: The beauty of the creative process made visible. This should look like a master artist's sketchbook page — not sloppy, but deliberately raw and unfinished. The energy of creation is more important than polish. Think Leonardo da Vinci study sketches.\nDETAIL: Variable. Some focal areas are more rendered and detailed, while peripheral areas fade into light sketch marks or disappear entirely. This selective finish creates visual hierarchy and the feeling of a work-in-progress.\nMARKS: Visible pencil/pen energy. Quick confident strokes. Gestural marks that capture movement and form. Erasure marks or ghost lines showing the construction process. The hand of the artist is always visible.\nCOMPOSITION: Subject isolated on white background. The sketch may be asymmetrically developed — more finished on one side, dissolving into loose marks on the other. Unfinished edges are part of the design.\nNEGATIVE: clean single outlines, smooth blending, photorealistic, polished finished look, bold filled outlines, flat color, watercolor wash, geometric precision, digital clean lines, perfect symmetry."],
  ["dark_art", "[SUBJECT].\nSTYLE: Dark Art / Horror tattoo. Macabre, unsettling, beautifully grotesque. Fine art darkness. Flat on white background.\nRENDERING: Highly detailed, semi-realistic to realistic rendering. Technical skill in service of dark subject matter. The quality of execution elevates the macabre content to fine art.\nSHADING: Predominantly dark tonal range. Heavy use of deep blacks and dark greys. Shadows are dense and consuming. Limited highlights used strategically for dramatic effect — bright points of light in overall darkness. High contrast chiaroscuro with dominant shadow.\nTEXTURE: Richly rendered dark textures: decaying surfaces, aged bone, dried blood, cracked skin, withered organic matter, rust, patina, cobwebs, dripping liquid, smoke and haze. Every surface tells a story of entropy and decay.\nATMOSPHERE: Oppressive, moody, ominous. The overall tonal weight should feel heavy and dark. A sense of dread, mystery, or supernatural unease permeates the design. Gothic cathedral atmosphere.\nDETAIL: Dense, intricate detail work especially in areas of texture and decay. Fine cracks in bone, individual teeth, delicate cobweb threads, subtle smoke wisps, tiny insects. The horror is in the details.\nAESTHETIC: References: Zdzisław Beksiński, H.R. Giger, Francisco Goya's dark paintings, Gustave Doré's Inferno illustrations, gothic horror illustration, memento mori tradition, vanitas still life.\nCOMPOSITION: Subject isolated on white background. The darkness of the rendering contrasts dramatically against the white, making the subject float in a void.\nNEGATIVE: bright colors, cute, cheerful, cartoon, minimal, clean, watercolor soft, pastel, geometric, tribal, simple, light-hearted, low detail."],
  ["tattoo_abstract", "[SUBJECT].\nSTYLE: Abstract tattoo. Non-representational or semi-abstract interpretation. Emotional expression over literal depiction. Flat on white background.\nLINEWORK: Expressive, dynamic lines with dramatic variation. Some lines bold and aggressive, others thin and delicate. Lines may be gestural, calligraphic, or chaotically energetic. The line quality itself carries emotion.\nTECHNIQUE: The subject is interpreted through abstract visual language: deconstructed forms, fragmented shapes, expressive brush strokes, ink splashes, flowing organic forms, sharp angular intersections. The subject should be suggested or evoked rather than literally depicted.\nCOLOR: If used, bold and expressive — not naturalistic. Colors chosen for emotional impact, not realism. Large fields of black, strategic use of white space, potential bold color accents. Color serves composition and emotion.\nCOMPOSITION: Dynamic, asymmetric, unconventional. May break traditional framing. Elements may extend, dissolve, or explode across the space. The arrangement itself is expressive.\nENERGY: The marks on the surface should convey energy, emotion, or movement. Every stroke feels intentional but spontaneous. Think Franz Kline, Robert Motherwell, or calligraphic abstract expressionism.\nSPACE: White background as active compositional element. The balance between mark and space is carefully orchestrated. Breathing room is essential.\nNEGATIVE: literal representational, photorealistic, traditional tattoo conventions, geometric precision, ornamental pattern, cute, decorative, predictable composition, tight controlled rendering."],
  ["patchwork", "[SUBJECT].\nSTYLE: Patchwork tattoo. Collection of small, separate, distinct designs arranged together like patches or stickers on skin. Flat on white background.\nLINEWORK: Each individual patch has its own clean, complete outline. Bold black borders around each small design element. Every patch is self-contained with its own complete outline. No patches overlap or merge.\nAESTHETIC: A curated collection of small tattoo flash designs arranged with intentional spacing between them. Each element is its own mini-tattoo — simple, iconic, immediately readable. Think scattered tattoo flash stickers on a white surface.\nINDIVIDUAL ELEMENTS: Each patch is small, simple, and uses a different mini-style or icon: tiny traditional flash, small symbols, mini animals, simple objects, food items, celestial objects, plants, tools. Each is complete and self-sufficient.\nSPACING: Visible white space gaps between every patch element. No elements touch or overlap. The gaps are consistent and deliberate — they're part of the design. The white space connects the collection.\nFILL: Individual patches may use flat color fills, simple black-and-grey, or just line work. Mixed approaches across different patches create visual variety and the authentic patchwork aesthetic.\nCOMPOSITION: Multiple small elements isolated on white background with consistent spacing. Arranged in an organic, casual scatter — not a rigid grid. Feels collected over time, not planned in one session.\nNEGATIVE: single unified design, realistic rendering, large scale, overlapping elements, no spacing, one continuous composition, complex shading, photorealistic, abstract."],
  ["cyber", "[SUBJECT].\nSTYLE: Cyberpunk / Futuristic tattoo. Sci-fi technology meets body art. Circuit board meets flesh. Flat on white background.\nLINEWORK: Precise, clean, technical lines. Circuit board traces, data flow paths, geometric tech patterns. Mix of organic subject outlines with overlaid technical/digital elements. Lines feel engineered, not hand-drawn.\nELEMENTS: Integrate futuristic technology elements: circuit board traces, data streams, binary code, holographic glitch effects, HUD overlay graphics, scanning grid lines, targeting reticles, loading bars, pixel fragments, digital noise artifacts.\nRENDERING: Clean, precise technical rendering. Subjects may be partially \"digitized\" — transitioning from organic form to wireframe, pixel grid, or data visualization. Glitch art effects: scan lines, RGB color split, data corruption artifacts.\nCOLOR: If color is used, cyberpunk palette: electric cyan, neon magenta, toxic green matrix code, orange warning accents against black and dark grey. Color should feel like it's emitting light — glowing neon on dark surface.\nTEXTURE: Clean and technical. Smooth surfaces, sharp edges, digital precision. Contrast between organic subject texture and clean digital overlay elements. Circuit board trace patterns, microchip textures, fiber optic strands.\nCOMPOSITION: Subject isolated on white background. Technology elements may extend beyond the subject in geometric data-flow patterns.\nNEGATIVE: traditional tattoo, vintage, organic flowing, watercolor, hand-drawn sketch, tribal, ornamental, warm tones, rustic, natural, soft, analog."],
  ["lettering", "[SUBJECT].\nSTYLE: Lettering / Script tattoo. Typography as art form. The subject interpreted through or accompanied by masterful hand-lettering. Flat on white background.\nLETTERFORMS: Expert hand-lettering — not a font. Every letter has the organic quality of hand-crafted calligraphy. Style may range from: flowing cursive script, bold block capitals, ornate Gothic blackletter, elaborate Victorian decorative, graffiti wildstyle, or elegant copperplate.\nTECHNIQUE: Letters rendered with full dimensional shading. Each letterform has weight, depth, and material quality — as if carved in stone, cast in metal, written in flowing ink, or chiseled in wood. Light and shadow make letters feel physical and tangible.\nDECORATION: Elaborate decorative flourishes, swashes, ornamental terminals, inline detail, drop shadows, dimensional bevels. Filigree extensions and connecting strokes between letters. The ornamentation elevates the lettering to fine art.\nINTEGRATION: If the subject is non-text, integrate lettering elements into or around the subject — text wrapping, flowing script emerging from the subject, letters formed by or transforming into the subject matter.\nCOMPOSITION: Subject isolated on white background. Lettering is the hero — it commands the composition. Decorative elements frame and support without overwhelming.\nNEGATIVE: digital font, plain undecorated text, flat 2D letters, inconsistent quality, rushed execution, minimal, small text, sans-serif simplicity."],
  ["micro_realism", "[SUBJECT].\nSTYLE: Micro Realism tattoo. Photorealistic rendering at miniature scale. Impossibly detailed tiny art. Flat on white background.\nSCALE: The subject is rendered small — as if the entire detailed image fits within a 2-3 inch space. Despite the small scale, detail density is extraordinary.\nRENDERING: Full photorealistic quality. Smooth tonal gradients, accurate lighting, material-specific textures. Indistinguishable from a tiny high-resolution photograph. Single-needle precision throughout.\nDETAIL: Microscopic precision within a compact composition. Fine textures, subtle tonal shifts, delicate highlights. Every square millimeter contains accurate rendered detail. The impossibility of this level of detail at this scale is the wow factor.\nSHADING: Ultra-smooth grey wash transitions. No visible stipple or grain. Silky blending from black through full grey range to white. Soft, photographic quality with no tattoo \"technique\" visible — just pure image.\nLINEWORK: No visible outlines. Form defined entirely by tonal value shifts. If any structural lines exist, they're so fine as to be invisible at normal viewing distance.\nCOMPOSITION: Subject isolated on white background. Compact composition that reads as a complete miniature photograph. Nothing wasted, nothing extraneous.\nNEGATIVE: large scale, bold outlines, visible technique, traditional style, rough texture, heavy black, graphic, abstract, cartoon, watercolor, tribal."],
  ["negative_space", "[SUBJECT].\nSTYLE: Negative Space tattoo. Subject defined by the absence of ink rather than its presence. Optical reversal technique. Flat on white background.\nCONCEPT: The primary subject is formed by un-inked white space carved out of a surrounding field of black (or heavy pattern). The subject appears as a white \"ghost\" or \"window\" within dense black surroundings. The brain reads the absence as the subject.\nFILL: Dense black ink or heavy pattern work forms the \"background\" or surrounding field. The subject exists as clean white channels, shapes, and details preserved within this dark field. The white IS the subject.\nTECHNIQUE: Think of it as carving white light out of darkness. Internal details of the subject are created by varying the width and shape of white channels within black. Fine white lines within black mass create texture and form.\nCONTRAST: Maximum contrast between dense black fields and clean white preserved areas. No grey middle ground — the power comes from the stark black-white reversal.\nEDGES: The outer boundary where the black field meets the white background can be: geometric (circle, triangle, diamond framing the design), organic (following the subject's natural silhouette), or abstract (irregular, dissolving).\nCOMPOSITION: Subject isolated on white background. The black field that contains the negative-space subject may be geometric, organic, or abstract in its outer shape.\nNEGATIVE: traditional positive rendering, outlined and filled subject, grey shading, color, watercolor, fine-line minimal, sketch, low contrast, realistic gradient shading."],
  ["anime", "[SUBJECT].\nSTYLE: Anime / Manga tattoo. Japanese animation and comic art aesthetic translated to tattoo. Flat on white background.\nLINEWORK: Clean, confident, black outlines with deliberate weight variation. Thicker on outer contours and shadow edges, thinner for fine details. Lines are smooth and precise with slight characteristic anime \"snap\" at corners. No sketch lines — final clean ink quality.\nEYES: If the subject has eyes, render in characteristic anime style: large, expressive, detailed with multiple highlights (large primary catch-light plus smaller secondary reflections), defined pupil and iris detail, emphasized eyelashes.\nSHADING: Clean cel-shading technique. Distinct shadow shapes with defined edges — not smooth gradients. Shadow tone sits as a flat darker value next to lit areas with a clean boundary between them. One or two shadow tones maximum. Crisp highlight shapes.\nCOLOR: If color, use vibrant anime palette — saturated but clean. Flat color fills within outlines with cel-shade shadow overlays. Hair often has distinct highlight streaks (anime hair shine). Skin tones warm and luminous.\nAESTHETIC: Reference quality anime/manga illustration: dynamic poses, expressive features, dramatic speed lines or impact frames, flowing hair and fabric, energy effects (aura, glow, particles). Studio Ghibli, Berserk, Akira, or shonen/seinen manga quality.\nRENDERING: Flat illustrative, NOT photorealistic. Cel-shaded dimensional but maintaining the graphic 2D quality that defines anime art. Clean and polished — production quality, not fan art.\nCOMPOSITION: Subject isolated on white background. Dynamic pose and composition. May include manga-style effects: speed lines, impact marks, floating particles, energy aura.\nNEGATIVE: photorealistic, western cartoon, rough sketch, watercolor loose, traditional tattoo bold, tribal, geometric abstract, chibi proportions (unless requested), sloppy linework, gradient airbrush shading."],
]);

